formation processing | journal = [[Educational Psychology Review]] | volume = 4 | issue = 3| pages = 271\u2013308 | doi=10.1007/bf01417874}}\n*Jensen, A.R. (1998). ''The ''g'' factor: The science of mental ability''. Westport, CT: Praeger. {{ISBN|0-275-96103-6}}\n*Jensen, A.R. (2000). [http://www.cogsci.ecs.soton.ac.uk/cgi/psyc/newpsy?11.088 A Nihilistic Philosophy of Science for a Scientific Psychology?] ''Psycoloquy, 11,'' Issue 088, Article 49.\n*Jensen, A.R. (2002). Psychometric g: Definition and substantiation. In R.J. Sternberg & E.L. Grigorenko (Eds.), ''General factor of intelligence: How general is it?'' (pp.&nbsp;39\u201354). Mahwah, NJ: Erlbaum.\n<!--*Jensen, A.R. (2005). Mental chronometry and the unification of differential psychology. In Sternberg, R.J. & Pretz, J. (Eds), ''Cognition and intelligence'' (pp. 26\u201350). Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.-->\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Johnson | first1 = W. | last2 = Bouchard | first2 = T.J. | last3 = Krueger | first3 = R.F. | last4 = McGue | first4 = M. | last5 = Gottesman | first5 = I.I. | year = 2004 | title = Just one ''g'': Consistent results from three test batteries | journal = Intelligence | volume = 32 | pages = 95\u2013107 | doi = 10.1016/S0160-2896(03)00062-X }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Johnson | first1 = W. | last2 = te Nijenhuis | first2 = J. | last3 = Bouchard Jr | first3 = T. | year = 2008 | title = Still just 1 g: Consistent results from five test batteries | journal = Intelligence | volume = 36 | pages = 81\u201395 | doi=10.1016/j.intell.2007.06.001}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Judge | first1 = T. A. | last2 = Jackson | first2 = C. L. | last3 = Shaw | first3 = J. C. | last4 = Scott | first4 = B. A. | last5 = Rich | first5 = B. L. | year = 2007 | title = Self-efficacy and work-related performance: The integral role of individual differences | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0c0fb061ac17f23520773efc68b539ab35e9a358| journal = Journal of Applied Psychology | volume = 92 | issue = 1| pages = 107\u2013127 | doi=10.1037/0021-9010.92.1.107 | pmid=17227155}}\n*Kamphaus, R.W., Winsor, A.P., Rowe, E.W., & Kim, S. (2005). A history of intelligence test interpretation. In D.P. Flanagan and P.L. Harrison (Eds.), ''Contemporary intellectual assessment: Theories, tests, and issues'' (2nd Ed.) (pp.&nbsp;23\u201338). New York: Guilford.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Kane | first1 = M. J. | last2 = Hambrick | first2 = D. Z. | last3 = Conway | first3 = A. R. A. | year = 2005 | title = Working memory capacity and fluid intelligence are strongly related constructs: Comment on Ackerman, Beier, and Boyle (2004) | url =http://libres.uncg.edu/ir/uncg/f/M_Kane_Working_2005.pdf | journal = Psychological Bulletin | volume = 131 | issue = 1| pages = 66\u201371 | doi=10.1037/0033-2909.131.1.66 | pmid=15631552}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Keith | first1 = T.Z. | last2 = Kranzler | first2 = J.H. | last3 = Flanagan | first3 = D.P. | year = 2001 | title = What does the Cognitive Assessment System (CAS) measure? Joint confirmatory factor analysis of the CAS and the Woodcock-Johnson Tests of Cognitive Ability (3rd Edition) | journal = School Psychology Review | volume = 30 | pages = 89\u2013119 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Korb | first1 = K. B. | year = 1994 | title = Stephen Jay Gould on intelligence | journal = Cognition | volume = 52 | issue = 2| pages = 111\u2013123 | doi = 10.1016/0010-0277(94)90064-7 | pmid = 7924200 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.22.9513 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Kovas | first1 = Y. | last2 = Plomin | first2 = R. | year = 2006 | title = Generalist genes: implications for the cognitive sciences | journal = Trends in Cognitive Sciences | volume = 10 | issue = 5| pages = 198\u2013203 | doi=10.1016/j.tics.2006.03.001 | pmid=16580870}}\n*Kvist, A. & Gustafsson, J.-E. (2008). The relation between fluid intelligence and the general factor as a function of cultural background: A test of Cattell's Investment theory. ''Intelligence 36, 422\u2013436.\n*Lautrey, J. (2002). Is there a general factor of cognitive development? In Sternberg, R.J. & Grigorenko, E.L. (Eds.), ''The general factor of intelligence: How general is it?'' Mahwah, NJ: Erlbaum.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Lubinski | first1 = D | year = 2009 | title = Exceptional Cognitive Ability: The Phenotype | journal = Behavior Genetics | volume = 39 | issue = 4| pages = 350\u2013358 | doi = 10.1007/s10519-009-9273-0 | pmid = 19424784 }}\n*Lynn, R. (2003). The Geography of Intelligence. In Nyborg, H. (ed.), ''The Scientific Study of General Intelligence: Tribute to Arthur R. Jensen'' (pp. 126\u2013146). Oxford: Pergamon.\n*Mackintosh, N.J. (2011). ''IQ and Human Intelligence''. Oxford, UK: Oxford University Press.\n*McGrew, K.S. (2005). The Cattell-Horn-Carroll Theory of Cognitive Abilities: Past, Present, and Future. Contemporary Intellectual Assessment: Theories, Tests, and Issues. (pp. 136\u2013181) New York, NY, US: Guilford Press Flanagan, Dawn P. (Ed); Harrison, Patti L. (Ed), (2005). xvii, 667 pp.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Neisser | first1 = U. | last2 = Boodoo | first2 = G. | last3 = Bouchard Jr | first3 = T.J. | last4 = Boykin | first4 = A.W. | last5 = Brody | first5 = N. | last6 = Ceci | first6 = S.J. | last7 = Halpern | first7 = D.F. | last8 = Loehlin | first8 = J.C. | last9 = Perloff | first9 = R. | year = 1996 | title = Intelligence: Knowns and Unknowns | journal = American Psychologist | volume = 51 | issue = 2| pages = 77\u2013101 | doi=10.1037/0003-066x.51.2.77| citeseerx = 10.1.1.322.5525 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Oberauer | first1 = K. | last2 = Schulze | first2 = R. | last3 = Wilhelm | first3 = O. | last4 = S\u00fc\u00df | first4 = H.-M. | year = 2005 | title = Working memory and intelligence \u2013 their correlation and their relation: A comment on Ackerman, Beier, and Boyle (2005) | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/d19f4a39eaeedc70e7229ce80db9af8163f7d43d| journal = Psychological Bulletin | volume = 131 | issue = 1| pages = 61\u201365 | doi=10.1037/0033-2909.131.1.61 | pmid=15631551}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Penke | first1 = L. | last2 = Denissen | first2 = J.J.A. | last3 = Miller | first3 = G.F. | year = 2007 | title = The Evolutionary Genetics of Personality | url = http://matthewckeller.com/Penke_EvoGenPersonality_2007.pdf | journal = European Journal of Personality | volume = 21 | issue = 5| pages = 549\u2013587 | doi=10.1002/per.629}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Plomin | first1 = R | year = 2003 | title = Genetics, genes, genomics and g. | journal = Molecular Psychiatry | volume = 8 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u20135 | doi=10.1038/sj.mp.4001249| pmid = 12556898 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Plomin | first1 = R. | last2 = Spinath | first2 = F.M. | year = 2004 | title = Intelligence: genetics, genes, and genomics | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/8be605ab07a01ceb0373a0cf8113747c5a80a16c| journal = J Pers Soc Psychol | volume = 86 | issue = 1| pages = 112\u2013129 | doi = 10.1037/0022-3514.86.1.112 | pmid = 14717631 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Robertson | first1 = K.F. | last2 = Smeets | first2 = S. | last3 = Lubinski | first3 = D. | last4 = Benbow | first4 = C.P. | year = 2010 | title = Beyond the Threshold Hypothesis: Even Among the Gifted and Top Math/Science Graduate Students, Cognitive Abilities, Vocational Interests, and Lifestyle Preferences Matter for Career Choice, Performance, and Persistence | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1105167599ed8a1fe800f1039a858073fe7e7edb| journal = Current Directions in Psychological Science | volume = 19 | issue = 6| pages = 346\u2013351 | doi=10.1177/0963721410391442}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Roth | first1 = P.L. | last2 = Bevier | first2 = C.A. | last3 = Bobko | first3 = P. | last4 = Switzer III | first4 = F.S. | last5 = Tyler | first5 = P. | year = 2001 | title = Ethnic group differences in cognitive ability in employment and educational settings: A meta-analysis | journal = Personnel Psychology | volume = 54 | issue = 2| pages = 297\u2013330 | doi=10.1111/j.1744-6570.2001.tb00094.x| citeseerx = 10.1.1.372.6092 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Rushton | first1 = J.P. | last2 = Jensen | first2 = A.R. | year = 2010 | title = The rise and fall of the Flynn Effect as a reason to expect a narrowing of the Black\u2013White IQ gap | journal = Intelligence | volume = 38 | issue = 2| pages = 213\u2013219 | doi = 10.1016/j.intell.2009.12.002 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Sackett | first1 = P.R. | last2 = Borneman | first2 = M.J. | last3 = Connelly | first3 = B.S. | year = 2008 | title = High-Stakes Testing in Higher Education and Employment. Appraising the Evidence for Validity and Fairness | journal = American Psychologist | volume = 63 | issue = 4| pages = 215\u2013227 | doi=10.1037/0003-066x.63.4.215 | pmid=18473607| citeseerx = 10.1.1.189.2163 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Schmidt | first1 = F.L. | last2 = Hunter | first2 = J. | year = 2004 | title = General Mental Ability in the World of Work: Occupational Attainment and Job Performance | url = http://www.unc.edu/~nielsen/soci708/cdocs/Schmidt_Hunter_2004.pdf | journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology | volume = 86 | issue = 1| pages = 162\u2013173 | doi=10.1037/0022-3514.86.1.162 | pmid=14717634| citeseerx = 10.1.1.394.8878 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Spearman | first1 = C.E. | year = 1904 | title = 'General intelligence', Objectively Determined And Measured | url = http://www.psych.umn.edu/faculty/waller/classes/FA2010/Readings/Spearman1904.pdf | journal = American Journal of Psychology | volume = 15 | issue =  2| pages = 201\u2013293 | doi = 10.2307/1412107 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140407100036/http://www.psych.umn.edu/faculty/waller/classes/FA2010/Readings/Spearman1904.pdf | archivedate = 7 April 2014 | df = dmy-all | jstor = 1412107 }}\n*Spearman, C.E. (1927). ''The Abilities of Man.'' London: Macmillan.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Stauffer | first1 = J. | last2 = Ree | first2 = M.J. | last3 = Carretta | first3 = T.R. | year = 1996 | title = Cognitive-Components Tests Are Not Much More than ''g'': An Extension of Kyllonen's Analyses | journal = The Journal of General Psychology | volume = 123 | issue = 3| pages = 193\u2013205 | doi=10.1080/00221309.1996.9921272}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Sternberg | first1 = R. J. | last2 = Conway | first2 = B. E. | last3 = Ketron | first3 = J. L. | last4 = Bernstein | first4 = M. | year = 1981 | title = People's conception of intelligence | journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology | volume = 41 | pages = 37\u201355 | doi = 10.1037/0022-3514.41.1.37 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = von Stumm | first1 = S. | last2 = Chamorro-Premuzic | first2 = T. | last3 = Quiroga | first3 = M.\u00c1. | last4 = Colom | first4 = R. | year = 2009 | title = Separating narrow and general variances in intelligence-personality associations | journal = Personality and Individual Differences | volume = 47 | issue = 4| pages = 336\u2013341 | doi=10.1016/j.paid.2009.03.024}}\n*von Stumm, S., Chamorro-Premuzic, T., Ackerman, P. L. (2011). Re-visiting intelligence-personality associations: Vindicating intellectual investment. In T. Chamorro-Premuzic, S. von Stumm, & A. Furnham (eds.), ''Handbook of Individual Differences''. Chichester, UK: Wiley-Blackwell.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Tucker-Drob | first1 = E.M. | year = 2009 | title = Differentiation of cognitive abilities across the life span | journal = Developmental Psychology | volume = 45 | issue = 4| pages = 1097\u20131118 | doi = 10.1037/a0015864 | pmid=19586182 | pmc=2855504}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = van der Maas | first1 = H. L. J. | last2 = Dolan | first2 = C. V. | last3 = Grasman | first3 = R. P. P. P. | last4 = Wicherts | first4 = J. M. | last5 = Huizenga | first5 = H. M. | last6 = Raaijmakers | first6 = M. E. J. | year = 2006 | title = A dynamical model of general intelligence: The positive manifold of intelligence by mutualism | url = http://wicherts.socsci.uva.nl/maas2006.pdf | journal = Psychological Review | volume = 13 | issue = 4 | pages = 842\u2013860 | doi = 10.1037/0033-295x.113.4.842 | pmid = 17014305 | access-date = 1 August 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120417015005/http://wicherts.socsci.uva.nl/maas2006.pdf | archive-date = 17 April 2012 | url-status = dead }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Weinberg | first1 = R.A. | year = 1989 | title = Intelligence and IQ. Landmark Issues and Great Debates | journal = American Psychologist | volume = 44 | issue = 2| pages = 98\u2013104 | doi = 10.1037/0003-066X.44.2.98 }}\n<!--*Wicherts, J.M., Dolan, C.V., Hessen, D.J., Oosterveld, P., Baal, G.C.M. van, Boomsma, D.I., & Span, M.M. (2004). [http://www.iapsych.com/iqmr/fe/LinkedDocuments/wicherts2004.pdf Are intelligence tests measurement invariant over time? Investigating the nature of the Flynn effect.] ''Intelligence'', 32, 509\u2013537.-->\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.udel.edu/educ/gottfredson/reprints/1998generalintelligencefactor.pdf ''The General Intelligence Factor'' by Linda S. Gottfredson ]\n\n{{Human intelligence topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:G factor}}\n[[Category:Intelligence]]\n[[Category:Intelligence tests]]\n[[Category:Psychometrics]]\n", "name_user": "CommonKnowledgeCreator", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSocial exchange:Page numbers correction on Tooby & Cosmides ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G_factor_(psychometrics)"}
{"title_page": "Visions of Johanna", "text_new": "{{Good Article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Visions of Johanna\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blonde on Blonde]]\n| released = June 20, 1966\n| format   =\n| recorded = February 14, 1966\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Folk rock]]\n| length   = 7:30\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer =\n| tracks   = {{Blonde on Blonde tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Visions of Johanna'''\" is a song written and performed by [[Bob Dylan]] on his 1966 album ''[[Blonde on Blonde]]''. Several critics have acclaimed \"Visions of Johanna\" as one of Dylan's highest achievements in writing,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-10-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-20110511/visions-of-johanna-20110511|title=10 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/bob-dylan-30-greatest-songs/visions-of-johanna/|title=Bob Dylan: 30 greatest songs|date=2015-07-24|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> praising the allusiveness and subtlety of the language.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://americansongwriter.com/2009/04/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-12-visions-of-johanna/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #12, \"Visions of Johanna\" \u00ab American Songwriter|date=2009-04-24|work=American Songwriter|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jonnythakkar.com/inside-out-essays/visions-of-infinity-bob-dylan-johanna/|title=Visions of Infinity \u00ab Jonny Thakkar|website=www.jonnythakkar.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' included \"Visions of Johanna\" on their list of [[the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]. In 1999, Sir [[Andrew Motion]], [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]], listed it as the greatest song lyric ever written.\n\nDylan first recorded the song in New York City in November 1965, under the working title of \"Freeze Out\", but was dissatisfied with the results. When the ''Blonde on Blonde'' recording sessions moved to Nashville in February 1966, Dylan attempted the composition again with different musicians, and decided to release this performance. All of the alternate versions of the song have been officially released, but some only on a limited edition collectors set: many of them are November 1965 or later 1966 studio [[outtakes]], and two others are live performances from his [[Bob Dylan World Tour 1966|1966 world tour]].\n\nNumerous artists have recorded [[cover version]]s of the song, including the [[Grateful Dead]], [[Marianne Faithfull]] and [[Robyn Hitchcock]].\n\n==Recording==\n[[Clinton Heylin]] places the writing of \"Visions of Johanna\" in the fall of 1965, when Dylan was living in the [[Hotel Chelsea|Chelsea Hotel]] with his pregnant wife [[Sara Dylan|Sara]]. Heylin notes that \"in this d\u00e9class\u00e9 hotel\u2026the heat pipes ''still'' cough\", referring to a line from the song.<ref name = \"Heylin273\">{{harvnb|Heylin|2009|pp=273\u2013279}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Visions of Johanna (Bobdylan.com)}}</ref> [[Greil Marcus]] reports that when the song was first released, \"the story was that the song had been written during the great [[Northeast blackout of 1965|east coast blackout of November 9, 1965]].\"<ref name = \"Marcus\">{{harvnb|Marcus|2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bob Dylan and The Band - 1974.jpg|thumb|left|Dylan performs with [[The Band]] on their [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|1974 tour]]. Dylan's first attempt to record \"Visions of Johanna\" in 1965 was backed by members of this group, known in their earlier incarnation as The Hawks.]]\nDylan first recorded this song, backed by [[The Band#With Bob Dylan|The Hawks]], in the CBS New York recording studio, on November 30, 1965, announcing his new composition with the words: \"This is called 'Freeze Out'.\"<ref name=\"Wilentz110\">{{harvnb|Wilentz|2009|pp=110\u2013113}}</ref> Andy Gill notes that this working title captures the \"air of nocturnal suspension in which the verse tableaux are sketched...full of whispering and muttering.\"<ref name=\"Gill97\">{{harvnb|Gill|1998|pp=97\u201399}}</ref> According to Marcus, Dylan introduced the song in live performances in 1966 with the words, \"Seems like a freeze-out.\"<ref name = \"Marcus\"/>\n\nSome of the New York recordings were uptempo and contain in the fifth verse the additional line \"He examines the nightingale's code\". Historian [[Sean Wilentz]], for his book ''Dylan In America'', listened closely to full studio tapes of the ''Blonde on Blonde'' sessions, and describes how Dylan guided the New York backing musicians through fourteen takes, trying to explain how he wanted \"Visions of Johanna\" played. At one point, Dylan says: \"It's not [[hard rock]], The only thing in it that's hard is [[Robbie Robertson|Robbie]].\" Analyzing the evolution of the song in the New York recording session, Wilentz writes that Dylan \"quiets things down, inching closer to what will eventually appear on ''Blonde on Blonde''\u2014and it is still not right.\"<ref name=\"Wilentz110\"/>  Several complete takes of the song<ref name = \"Heylin277\">{{harvnb|Heylin|2009|p=277}}</ref> were recorded on November 30, including one with an uptempo rock beat, containing harpsichord accompaniment, and another with a march-like tempo, which was released on ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 7: No Direction Home: The Soundtrack]]'' in 2005.<ref>{{harvnb|Gorodetsky|2005}}</ref>\n\n{{Listen|filename=Visions_Of_Johanna.ogg|title=Visions of Johanna|description=Describing \"Visions of Johanna\" as \"Dylan's most haunting and complex love song and his finest poem\", [[Robert Shelton (critic)|Robert Shelton]] suggests that Dylan \"constantly seeks to transcend the physical world, to reach the ideal where the visions of Johanna become real\".<ref name=\"Shelton225\">{{harvnb|Shelton|2011|p=225}}</ref>}}\"Visions of Johanna\" fell into place when Dylan was persuaded by his producer, [[Bob Johnston]], to move the recording sessions to [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. During his first day in the CBS Nashville studio, on February 14, 1966, the ''Blonde on Blonde'' version of the song was recorded. In an interview with Andy Gill, [[Al Kooper]] has said that he and guitarist Robbie Robertson became sensitive to the nuances of Dylan's vocal.<ref name=\"Gill97\"/> Kooper added that \"it's very important what [[Joe South|Joe South's]] bass is doing in that\"; Kooper described it as \"this throbbing...rhythmically amazing bass part\".<ref name=\"Gill97\"/> Other backing musicians were [[Charlie McCoy]], guitar, [[Wayne Moss]], guitar, and [[Kenneth Buttrey]] on drums.<ref>{{harvnb|Bj\u00f6rner|2011}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances and studio outtakes==\n[[File:Ginsberg-dylan.jpg|thumb|250px|Dylan plays a song to Allen Ginsberg during the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]] of 1975. Ginsberg's poetic technique has been cited as an influence on Dylan at the time he wrote \"Visions of Johanna\".]]\nDylan first performed \"Visions of Johanna\" in public on December 4, 1965, at the [[Berkeley Community Theatre]]. Present at this concert was [[Joan Baez]], who believed the lyrics referred to her. She said, \"He'd just written 'Visions of Johanna', which sounded very suspicious to me...he'd never performed it before and [[Bobby Neuwirth|Neuwirth]] told him I was there that night and he performed it.\"<ref name = \"Heylin275\">{{harvnb|Heylin|2009|p=275}}</ref> Heylin suggests that if Dylan performed it for anyone that night it was [[Allen Ginsberg]], who was also present. Heylin argues Dylan considered Ginsberg to be an important influence on his songwriting at this juncture, and was keen to showcase the song for the [[Beat Generation|Beat poet]].<ref name = \"Heylin275\"/>\n\nAll live versions of the song recorded during Dylan's 1966 tour of England have been released. Dylan's performance of the song at [[London]]'s [[Royal Albert Hall]] on May 26, 1966, appeared on ''[[Biograph (album)|Biograph]]'', released in 1985. Asked by [[Cameron Crowe]], for the liner notes for ''Biograph'', how he could remember the words of such a complex song in live performance, Dylan responded, \"I could remember a song without writing it down because it was so visual.\"<ref name = \"Crowe\">{{harvnb|Crowe|1985}}</ref> A performance of the song recorded at the [[Manchester]] [[Free Trade Hall]] on May 17, 1966, was released on ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 4: Bob Dylan Live 1966, The \"Royal Albert Hall\" Concert|The Bootleg Series Vol. 4: Bob Dylan Live 1966]]'' in 1998.<ref>{{harvnb|Glover|1998}}</ref>  In addition, a May 6, 1966, performance of the song, recorded in Belfast, was included on ''Live 1962-1966: Rare Performances From The Copyright Collections'', released in 2018.\n\nOn November 11, 2016, [[Legacy Recordings]] released a 36-CD boxed set, ''[[The 1966 Live Recordings]]'', which comprises every known recording of Bob Dylan\u2019s 1966 concert tour.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-bob-dylan-1966-live-recordings-20160927-snap-story.html| title = All of Bob Dylan's 1966 live shows in 36-CD box set due Nov. 11| author = Lewis, Randy| date = September 27, 2016| accessdate = September 28, 2016| work = Los Angeles Times}}</ref> The recordings commence with the concert in White Plains, New York on February 5, 1966, and end with the [[Royal Albert Hall]] concert in London on May 27. The set contains 18 live performances of \"Visions of Johanna\", all featuring Dylan solo on acoustic guitar.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-1966-live-recordings-mw0002986802| title = The 1966 Live Recordings| author = Erlewine, Stephen Thomas\n| date = November 11, 2016| accessdate = December 2, 2016| publisher = allmusic.com}}</ref>  (The May 26, 1966, performance was included on the separately released album ''The Real Royal Albert Hall 1966 Concert''.)\n\nThe \"Visions of Johanna\" studio recording sessions were released in their entirety on the 18-disc Collector's Edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 12: The Cutting Edge 1965\u20131966]]'' on November 6, 2015, with highlights from the November 30, 1965, outtakes appearing on the 6-disc and 2-disc versions of that album.<ref name =Tracks>{{cite web|title=Bob Dylan - The Cutting Edge 1965-1966: The Bootleg Series Vol. 12|url=http://bobdylan.com/thecuttingedge_completetracklisting/|accessdate=2016-12-02}}</ref> The 18-disc version contains 14 takes of \"Visions of Johanna\" recorded in New York on November 30, 1965, and 4 takes of the song recorded in Nashville on February 14, 1966, the last being the ''Blonde on Blonde'' version of the song.<ref name =Tracks/>\n\n==Interpretation==\nNoting how popular \"Visions of Johanna\" remains among \"hardcore Dylanophiles,\" Andy Gill suggests it is the enigmatic quality of the song that is responsible for its popularity&mdash;\"forever teetering on the brink of lucidity, yet remaining impervious to strict decipherment\".<ref name=\"Gill97\"/> Gill writes that the song begins by contrasting two lovers, the carnal Louise, and \"the more spiritual but unattainable\" Johanna. Ultimately, for Gill, the song seeks to convey how the artist is compelled to keep striving to pursue some elusive vision of perfection.<ref name=\"Gill97\"/>\n\nClinton Heylin has described what he construes as the strange circumstances surrounding the song. Written around the time of Dylan's marriage to Sara Lownds, Heylin describes it as \"one of the oddest songs ever written by a man who has just tied the knot and is enjoying a brief honeymoon in the city\".<ref name = \"Heylin273\"/> Noting that the song is an elegy for a past lover, Heylin speculates that \"it is awfully tempting to see Johanna as his muse,\" who, in the song, is \"not here\". For Heylin, the triumph of the song lies in \"the way Dylan manages to write about the most inchoate feelings in such a vivid, immediate way\".<ref name = \"Heylin273\"/>\n\nDylan critic [[Michael Gray (author)|Michael Gray]] also praises the subtlety of the song. Gray acknowledges that it is difficult to say what this song is \"about\", since it is at once indefinable and precise. For Gray, its principal achievement lies in the way it confuses categories, using language to be simultaneously serious and flippant, delicate and coarse, and mixing up \"abstract neo-philosophy and figurative phraseology\".<ref>{{harvnb|Gray|2000|pp=154\u2013155}}</ref>\n\nRobert Shelton called \"Visions of Johanna\" one of Dylan's major works. He writes that Dylan's technique of throwing out \"skittering images\" evokes \"a mind floating downstream\"; these \"non-sequential visions\" are the record of a fractured consciousness.<ref name=\"Shelton225\"/> Shelton argues that the song explores a hopeless quest to reach an ideal, the visions of Johanna, and yet without this quest life becomes meaningless. He suggests that the same paradox is explored by [[John Keats|Keats]] in his \"[[Ode on a Grecian Urn]]\".<ref name=\"Shelton225\"/>\n\n[[Mike Marqusee]] situates the song in New York City, \"a flickering, electric, ghostly, cityscape\".<ref name=marqusee206-207>{{harvnb|Marqusee|2005|pp=206\u2013207}}</ref> Dylan describes himself stranded in a fog of detachment which provides a haven, and at the same time is pained by a piercing clarity: an unmediated response that is \"too concise and too clear\". For Marqusee, Dylan describes his predicament, suspended between freedom and slavery, yet hungry for an authentic experience. Johanna and Louise are objects of desire and yearning. \"It is their elusiveness and unreality that's the point.\"<ref name=marqusee206-207/>\n\nGuitarist and critic [[Bill Janovitz]] also emphasizes the urban, unreal quality of \"Visions of Johanna\", calling it a \"sprawling epic\". \"The journey takes Dylan through lofts, the D train, a museum, empty lots, and through snippets of overheard conversation, as well as a discussion with some 'little boy lost', who 'takes himself so seriously', and who is 'so useless and all/muttering small talk at the wall'.\" For Janovitz, this  could \"possibly be a swipe at a critic\".<ref name=\"AllMusicJanovitz\">{{harvnb|Janovitz||}}</ref>\n\nLiterary critic [[Christopher Ricks]], in his study of Dylan's work, pinpoints the emotional effect of these same lines:\n\n::::''He\u2019s sure got a lotta gall to be so useless and all''\n::::''Muttering small talk at the wall while I\u2019m in the hall''\n\nRicks writes that the phrase \"and all\" turns a mood of helplessness into a sense of \"aggression and baffled anger\".<ref>{{harvnb|Ricks|2003|pp=487\u2013488}}</ref>\n\nTrying to unravel the mystery of the song, Greil Marcus writes that the song is concerned with internal questions, rather than external ones: \"Line by line, 'Blowin' in the Wind' is pious, or falsely innocent\u2014isn't it obvious that whoever wrote \"Yes, 'n' how many seas must a white dove sail / Before she sleeps in the sand?\" already knows the answer, assuming he, or anyone, can actually bring themselves to care about such a precious question? But 'Visions of Johanna' is asking different sorts of questions. Such as: Where are you? Who are you? What are you doing here?\" Evoking the drugged, urban milieu of the song, Marcus writes of \"People wandering from one corner of a loft to another, doped, drunk, half-awake, fast asleep, no point to the next breath, let alone the next step.\" For Marcus, \"'Visions of Johanna' makes a narrative solely out of atmosphere.\"<ref name = \"Marcus\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe song has been described by several critics as a masterpiece.<ref name = \"Heylin273\"/><ref name=\"Wilentz110\"/><ref name=\"Gill97\"/> In 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine placed the song at No.&nbsp;404 on their list of [[the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]],<ref>{{harvnb|500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2004): 401\u2013500}}</ref> commenting that Dylan \"never sounded lonelier than in this seven-minute ballad, cut in a single take on Valentine's Day 1966.\" (When ''Rolling Stone'' updated their list in 2010, the song dropped to No.&nbsp;413.)<ref>{{harvnb|500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2010): #413 \"Visions of Johanna\"}}</ref> In 1999, Britain's Poet Laureate, [[Andrew Motion]], chose it as his candidate for the best song lyric ever written. Motion praised \"the concentration and surprise\" of Dylan's lyrics, and said that, although he distanced himself from some of the singer's views about women, the \"rasp of his anger\" was a part of his greatness.<ref>{{harvnb|Thorpe|1999}}</ref> In 2017, the International Observer named the song the second best ever recorded,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.intobserver.com/the-international-observers-100-greatest-songs-of-all-time/|title=The International Observer's 100 Greatest Songs of All Time.|website=www.intobserver.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716222322/http://www.intobserver.com/the-international-observers-100-greatest-songs-of-all-time/|archive-date=2017-07-16|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-06-14}}</ref> stating, \"The 24 year old Dylan was beginning to realize that no matter how many perfect songs he wrote he could not achieve immortality through his art as he perhaps once believed, because even if people were still listening to the music in 500 years, he would still be dead.\" In an interview with ''[[The Independent]]'' in 1992, cult British musician [[Robyn Hitchcock]] described the song by saying \"it's pretty much the reason I'm a singer\".<ref>[https://durianapocalypse.net/archive/92/013092.html]</ref> Commenting on the song in a 1985 interview, Dylan said, \"I still sing that song every once in a while. It still stands up now as it did then, maybe even more in some kind of weird way.\"<ref name = \"Crowe\"/>\n\n==Cover versions==\n[[File:Grateful Dead - Jerry Garcia.jpg|thumb|Jerry Garcia recorded \"Visions of Johanna\" both as a solo artist and as a member of the Grateful Dead.]]\nThe [[Grateful Dead]] played \"Visions of Johanna\" in concert a number of times between 1986 and 1995,<ref>{{harvnb|Visions of Johanna (Dead.net)}}</ref> and both they and [[Jerry Garcia]] solo each released a live version on record.<ref>{{harvnb|Ruhlmann}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Planer: Garcia Plays Dylan}}</ref> There is also a 16-minute studio version of the song on Jerry Garcia's ''All Good Things Redux'', a bonus CD provided with the ''[[All Good Things: Jerry Garcia Studio Sessions|All Good Things]]'' box set of Garcia's studio recordings.<ref>{{harvnb|Planer: All Good Things Redux}}</ref>\n\nOther artists who have covered the song include [[Marianne Faithfull]],<ref>{{harvnb|Thompson}}</ref> [[Robyn Hitchcock]],<ref>{{harvnb|Downing}}</ref> [[Lee Ranaldo]],<ref>{{harvnb|Bush}}</ref> [[Chris Smither]],<ref>{{harvnb|Whitman}}</ref> former [[Flamin' Groovies]] guitarist [[Chris Wilson (guitarist)|Chris Wilson]],<ref>{{harvnb|Second Life: Overview}}</ref> [[Julie Felix]],<ref>{{harvnb|Julie Felix: Discography}}</ref> [[Maggie Holland]],<ref>{{harvnb|Getting There: Overview}}</ref> and [[50 Years of Blonde on Blonde|Old Crow Medicine Show]]. The jazz trio [[Michael Moore (saxophonist and clarinetist)|Jewels and Binoculars]], who named themselves after a phrase from \"Visions of Johanna\",<ref>{{harvnb|Ratliff|2008}}</ref> recorded an instrumental treatment of the song on their album ''The Music of Bob Dylan''.<ref>{{harvnb|Layne}}</ref> Foreign language versions of the song include a recording by [[Jan Erik Vold]], K\u00e5re Virud and Telemark Blueslag in Norwegian,<ref>{{harvnb|Bj\u00f6rner|2003}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stein Regn}}</ref> [[Gerard Quintana]]'s and Jordi Batiste's version in Catalan,<ref>{{harvnb|Sense reina ni as}}</ref> [[Steffen Brandt]]'s in Danish,<ref>{{harvnb|Baby Blue\u2014Bob Dylan Gendigtet: Overview}}</ref> and [[Ernst Jansz]]'s in Dutch.<ref>{{harvnb|Dromen Van Johanna}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/baby-blue-bob-dylan-gendigtet-r1711545|title=Baby Blue\u2014Bob Dylan Gendigtet: Overview|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Baby Blue\u2014Bob Dylan Gendigtet: Overview}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Olof|last=Bj\u00f6rner| authorlink=Olof  Bj\u00f6rner|url=http://www.bjorner.com/songsv.htm|title=It Ain't Me, Babe: Covers sorted by song name: V|work=Bjorner.com|date=2003-01-28|accessdate=2011-11-21|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Olof|last=Bj\u00f6rner| url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN01225%20(66).htm#_Toc476200867|title=The 6th Blonde On Blonde session, produced by Bob Johnston|work=Bjorner.com|date=2011-06-03|accessdate=2011-09-27|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=John|last=Bush|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/outlaw-blues-vol-2-r239878/review|title=Outlaw Blues, Vol. 2: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-11-20|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Al|last=Campbell|url=http://allmusic.com/album/blues-on-blonde-on-blonde-r635845/review|title=Blues on Blonde on Blonde: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite AV media notes|first=Cameron|last=Crowe|year=1985|publisher=Columbia Records|location=New York| title=Biograph|others=Bob Dylan|type=booklet|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Brian|last=Downing|url=http://allmusic.com/album/robyn-sings-r614586|title=Robyn Sings: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.ernstjansz.com/albumdromenvanjohanna.htm|title=Dromen Van Johanna|work=Ernstjansz.com|language=Dutch|accessdate=2011-10-17|ref={{SfnRef|Dromen Van Johanna}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/5|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2004): 401\u2013500|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2011-11-11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080625061023/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/5|archivedate=2008-06-22|ref={{SfnRef|500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2004): 401\u2013500}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/bob-dylan-visions-of-johanna-19691231|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2010): #413 \"Visions of Johanna\"|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2011-11-11|ref={{SfnRef|500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2010): #413 \"Visions of Johanna\"}}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106105303/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/bob-dylan-visions-of-johanna-19691231|archive-date=2011-11-06|url-status=dead}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/getting-there-r893305|title=Getting There: Overview|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Getting There: Overview}}}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Andy|last=Gill|title=Classic Bob Dylan: My Back Pages|publisher=Carlton|year=1998|isbn= 1-85868-599-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite AV media notes|first=Tony|last=Glover|year=1998|publisher=Columbia Records|location=New York| title=The Bootleg Series Vol. 4: Bob Dylan Live 1966, The \"Royal Albert Hall\" Concert|others=Bob Dylan|type=booklet|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n* {{cite AV media notes|first=Eddie|last=Gorodetsky|year=2005|publisher=Columbia Records|location=New York| title=No Direction Home: The Soundtrack\u2014The Bootleg Series Volume 7|others=Bob Dylan|type=booklet|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Michael|last=Gray|authorlink=Michael Gray (author)|title=Song & Dance Man III: The Art of Bob Dylan|publisher=Continuum International|year=2000|ref=harv|isbn=0-8264-5150-0}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Clinton|last=Heylin|title=Revolution In The Air: The Songs of Bob Dylan, Volume One: 1957\u201373 |publisher=Constable|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84901-051-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Bill|last=Janovitz|url=http://allmusic.com/song/visions-of-johanna-t1944340|title=Visions of Johanna: Song Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-11-01|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.knibbworld.com/juliefelix/records.htm|title=Julie Felix: Discography|work=Knibbworld.com|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Julie Felix: Discography}}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608142342/http://www.knibbworld.com/juliefelix/records.htm|archive-date=2012-06-08|url-status=dead}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Joslyn|last=Layne|url=http://allmusic.com/album/jewels-and-binoculars-the-music-of-bob-dylan-r565462|title=Jewels and Binoculars\u2014The Music of Bob Dylan: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Greil|last=Marcus|url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jun/21/folk.culture|title=Bob Dylan's Dream|date=2008-06-21|accessdate = 2011-11-07|work=The Guardian|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Mike|last=Marqusee|title=Wicked Messenger: Bob Dylan and the 1960s|publisher=Seven Stories Press|year=2005|isbn=978-1-58322-686-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Lindsay|last=Planer|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/all-good-things-redux-mw0001391968|title=All Good Things Redux: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2013-10-05|ref={{SfnRef|Planer: All Good Things Redux}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Lindsay|last=Planer|url=http://allmusic.com/album/garcia-plays-dylan-r796966/review|title=Garcia Plays Dylan: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Planer: Garcia Plays Dylan}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Ben|last=Ratliff| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/23/arts/music/23jewe.html| title=Dylan Without the Lyrics, Just the Melodies in Mind|work=The New York Times| date=2008-04-23|accessdate =2011-10-24|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Christopher|last=Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|publisher=Penguin/Viking|year=2003|isbn=0-670-80133-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=William|last=Ruhlmann|url=http://allmusic.com/album/fallout-from-the-phil-zone-r277543/review|title=Fallout from the Phil Zone: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/second-life-r1506417|title=Second Life: Overview|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Second Life: Overview}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.musicaglobal.com/en/pl42/id101/discs/sense-reina-ni-as.htm|title=Sense reina ni as|work=Musicaglobal.com|language=Catalan|accessdate=2011-11-08|ref={{SfnRef|Sense reina ni as}}}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Robert|last=Shelton|title=No Direction Home: The Life and Music of Bob Dylan, Revised & updated edition |publisher=Omnibus Press|year=2011|isbn=978-1-84938-911-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.recordheaven.net/index.cfm?x=browseArtist&ID=16139&iID=81398&sc=&ob=dt&so=ASC&pp=50&pn=1&sl=false|title=Stein Regn|work=Recordheaven.net|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2011-11-21|ref={{SfnRef|Stein Regn}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Dave|last=Thompson|url=http://allmusic.com/album/rich-kid-blues-r37131|title=Rich Kid Blues: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Vanessa|last=Thorpe|url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/oct/03/vanessathorpe.theobserver1|title=Laureate gives laurels to Dylan|date=1999-10-03|accessdate = 2011-07-29|work=The Observer|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/visions-of-johanna|title=Visions of Johanna|work=Bobdylan.com|accessdate=2011-11-05|ref={{SfnRef|Visions of Johanna (Bobdylan.com)}}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111024235711/http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/visions-of-johanna|archive-date=2011-10-24|url-status=dead}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.dead.net/song/visions-johanna|title=Visions of Johanna|work=Dead.net|accessdate=2011-10-26|ref={{SfnRef|Visions of Johanna (Dead.net)}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Andy|last=Whitman|url=http://allmusic.com/album/leave-the-light-on-r847882|title=Leave the Light On: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Sean|last=Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan In America|publisher=The Bodley Head|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84792-150-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bobdylan.com/us/songs/visions-johanna Lyrics of \"Visions of Johanna\"]\n\n{{Bob Dylan}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Bob Dylan]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bob Johnston]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good Article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Visions of Johanna\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blonde on Blonde]]\n| released = June 20, 1966\n| format   =\n| recorded = February 14, 1966\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Folk rock]]\n| length   = 7:30\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer =\n| tracks   = {{Blonde on Blonde tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Visions of Johanna'''\" is a song written and performed by [[Bob Dylan]] on his 1966 album ''[[Blonde on Blonde]]''. Several critics have acclaimed \"Visions of Johanna\" as one of Dylan's highest achievements in writing,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-10-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-20110511/visions-of-johanna-20110511|title=10 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/bob-dylan-30-greatest-songs/visions-of-johanna/|title=Bob Dylan: 30 greatest songs|date=2015-07-24|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> praising the allusiveness and subtlety of the language.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://americansongwriter.com/2009/04/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-12-visions-of-johanna/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #12, \"Visions of Johanna\" \u00ab American Songwriter|date=2009-04-24|work=American Songwriter|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jonnythakkar.com/inside-out-essays/visions-of-infinity-bob-dylan-johanna/|title=Visions of Infinity \u00ab Jonny Thakkar|website=www.jonnythakkar.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' included \"Visions of Johanna\" on their list of [[the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]. In 1999, Sir [[Andrew Motion]], [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]], listed it as the greatest song lyric ever written.\n\nDylan first recorded the song in New York City in November 1965, under the working title of \"Freeze Out\", but was dissatisfied with the results. When the ''Blonde on Blonde'' recording sessions moved to Nashville in February 1966, Dylan attempted the composition again with different musicians, and decided to release this performance. All of the alternate versions of the song have been officially released, but some only on a limited edition collectors set: many of them are November 1965 or later 1966 studio [[outtakes]], and two others are live performances from his [[Bob Dylan World Tour 1966|1966 world tour]].\n\nNumerous artists have recorded [[cover version]]s of the song, including the [[Grateful Dead]], [[Marianne Faithfull]] and [[Robyn Hitchcock]].\n\n==Recording==\n[[Clinton Heylin]] places the writing of \"Visions of Johanna\" in the fall of 1965, when Dylan was living in the [[Hotel Chelsea|Chelsea Hotel]] with his pregnant wife [[Sara Dylan|Sara]]. Heylin notes that \"in this d\u00e9class\u00e9 hotel\u2026the heat pipes ''still'' cough\", referring to a line from the song.<ref name = \"Heylin273\">{{harvnb|Heylin|2009|pp=273\u2013279}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Visions of Johanna (Bobdylan.com)}}</ref> [[Greil Marcus]] reports that when the song was first released, \"the story was that the song had been written during the great [[Northeast blackout of 1965|east coast blackout of November 9, 1965]].\"<ref name = \"Marcus\">{{harvnb|Marcus|2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bob Dylan and The Band - 1974.jpg|thumb|left|Dylan performs with [[The Band]] on their [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|1974 tour]]. Dylan's first attempt to record \"Visions of Johanna\" in 1965 was backed by members of this group, known in their earlier incarnation as The Hawks.]]\nDylan first recorded this song, backed by [[The Band#With Bob Dylan|The Hawks]], in the CBS New York recording studio, on November 30, 1965, announcing his new composition with the words: \"This is called 'Freeze Out'.\"<ref name=\"Wilentz110\">{{harvnb|Wilentz|2009|pp=110\u2013113}}</ref> Andy Gill notes that this working title captures the \"air of nocturnal suspension in which the verse tableaux are sketched...full of whispering and muttering.\"<ref name=\"Gill97\">{{harvnb|Gill|1998|pp=97\u201399}}</ref> According to Marcus, Dylan introduced the song in live performances in 1966 with the words, \"Seems like a freeze-out.\"<ref name = \"Marcus\"/>\n\nSome of the New York recordings were uptempo and contain in the fifth verse the additional line \"He examines the nightingale's code\". Historian [[Sean Wilentz]], for his book ''Dylan In America'', listened closely to full studio tapes of the ''Blonde on Blonde'' sessions, and describes how Dylan guided the New York backing musicians through fourteen takes, trying to explain how he wanted \"Visions of Johanna\" played. At one point, Dylan says: \"It's not [[hard rock]], The only thing in it that's hard is [[Robbie Robertson|Robbie]].\" Analyzing the evolution of the song in the New York recording session, Wilentz writes that Dylan \"quiets things down, inching closer to what will eventually appear on ''Blonde on Blonde''\u2014and it is still not right.\"<ref name=\"Wilentz110\"/>  Several complete takes of the song<ref name = \"Heylin277\">{{harvnb|Heylin|2009|p=277}}</ref> were recorded on November 30, including one with an uptempo rock beat, containing harpsichord accompaniment, and another with a march-like tempo, which was released on ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 7: No Direction Home: The Soundtrack]]'' in 2005.<ref>{{harvnb|Gorodetsky|2005}}</ref>\n\n{{Listen|filename=Visions_Of_Johanna.ogg|title=Visions of Johanna|description=Describing \"Visions of Johanna\" as \"Dylan's most haunting and complex love song and his finest poem\", [[Robert Shelton (critic)|Robert Shelton]] suggests that Dylan \"constantly seeks to transcend the physical world, to reach the ideal where the visions of Johanna become real\".<ref name=\"Shelton225\">{{harvnb|Shelton|2011|p=225}}</ref>}}\"Visions of Johanna\" fell into place when Dylan was persuaded by his producer, [[Bob Johnston]], to move the recording sessions to [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. During his first day in the CBS Nashville studio, on February 14, 1966, the ''Blonde on Blonde'' version of the song was recorded. In an interview with Andy Gill, [[Al Kooper]] has said that he and guitarist Robbie Robertson became sensitive to the nuances of Dylan's vocal.<ref name=\"Gill97\"/> Kooper added that \"it's very important what [[Joe South|Joe South's]] bass is doing in that\"; Kooper described it as \"this throbbing...rhythmically amazing bass part\".<ref name=\"Gill97\"/> Other backing musicians were [[Charlie McCoy]], guitar, [[Wayne Moss]], guitar, and [[Kenneth Buttrey]] on drums.<ref>{{harvnb|Bj\u00f6rner|2011}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances and studio outtakes==\n[[File:Ginsberg-dylan.jpg|thumb|250px|Dylan plays a song to Allen Ginsberg during the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]] of 1975. Ginsberg's poetic technique has been cited as an influence on Dylan at the time he wrote \"Visions of Johanna\".]]\nDylan first performed \"Visions of Johanna\" in public on December 4, 1965, at the [[Berkeley Community Theatre]]. Present at this concert was [[Joan Baez]], who believed the lyrics referred to her. She said, \"He'd just written 'Visions of Johanna', which sounded very suspicious to me...he'd never performed it before and [[Bobby Neuwirth|Neuwirth]] told him I was there that night and he performed it.\"<ref name = \"Heylin275\">{{harvnb|Heylin|2009|p=275}}</ref> Heylin suggests that if Dylan performed it for anyone that night it was [[Allen Ginsberg]], who was also present. Heylin argues Dylan considered Ginsberg to be an important influence on his songwriting at this juncture, and was keen to showcase the song for the [[Beat Generation|Beat poet]].<ref name = \"Heylin275\"/>\n\nAll live versions of the song recorded during Dylan's 1966 tour of England have been released. Dylan's performance of the song at [[London]]'s [[Royal Albert Hall]] on May 26, 1966, appeared on ''[[Biograph (album)|Biograph]]'', released in 1985. Asked by [[Cameron Crowe]], for the liner notes for ''Biograph'', how he could remember the words of such a complex song in live performance, Dylan responded, \"I could remember a song without writing it down because it was so visual.\"<ref name = \"Crowe\">{{harvnb|Crowe|1985}}</ref> A performance of the song recorded at the [[Manchester]] [[Free Trade Hall]] on May 17, 1966, was released on ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 4: Bob Dylan Live 1966, The \"Royal Albert Hall\" Concert|The Bootleg Series Vol. 4: Bob Dylan Live 1966]]'' in 1998.<ref>{{harvnb|Glover|1998}}</ref>  In addition, a May 6, 1966, performance of the song, recorded in Belfast, was included on ''Live 1962-1966: Rare Performances From The Copyright Collections'', released in 2018.\n\nOn November 11, 2016, [[Legacy Recordings]] released a 36-CD boxed set, ''[[The 1966 Live Recordings]]'', which comprises every known recording of Bob Dylan\u2019s 1966 concert tour.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-bob-dylan-1966-live-recordings-20160927-snap-story.html| title = All of Bob Dylan's 1966 live shows in 36-CD box set due Nov. 11| author = Lewis, Randy| date = September 27, 2016| accessdate = September 28, 2016| work = Los Angeles Times}}</ref> The recordings commence with the concert in White Plains, New York on February 5, 1966, and end with the [[Royal Albert Hall]] concert in London on May 27. The set contains 18 live performances of \"Visions of Johanna\", all featuring Dylan solo on acoustic guitar.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-1966-live-recordings-mw0002986802| title = The 1966 Live Recordings| author = Erlewine, Stephen Thomas\n| date = November 11, 2016| accessdate = December 2, 2016| publisher = allmusic.com}}</ref>  (The May 26, 1966, performance was included on the separately released album ''The Real Royal Albert Hall 1966 Concert''.)\n\nThe \"Visions of Johanna\" studio recording sessions were released in their entirety on the 18-disc Collector's Edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 12: The Cutting Edge 1965\u20131966]]'' on November 6, 2015, with highlights from the November 30, 1965, outtakes appearing on the 6-disc and 2-disc versions of that album.<ref name =Tracks>{{cite web|title=Bob Dylan - The Cutting Edge 1965-1966: The Bootleg Series Vol. 12|url=http://bobdylan.com/thecuttingedge_completetracklisting/|accessdate=2016-12-02}}</ref> The 18-disc version contains 14 takes of \"Visions of Johanna\" recorded in New York on November 30, 1965, and 4 takes of the song recorded in Nashville on February 14, 1966, the last being the ''Blonde on Blonde'' version of the song.<ref name =Tracks/>\n\n==Interpretation==\nNoting how popular \"Visions of Johanna\" remains among \"hardcore Dylanophiles,\" Andy Gill suggests it is the enigmatic quality of the song that is responsible for its popularity&mdash;\"forever teetering on the brink of lucidity, yet remaining impervious to strict decipherment\".<ref name=\"Gill97\"/> Gill writes that the song begins by contrasting two lovers, the carnal Louise, and \"the more spiritual but unattainable\" Johanna. Ultimately, for Gill, the song seeks to convey how the artist is compelled to keep striving to pursue some elusive vision of perfection.<ref name=\"Gill97\"/>\n\nClinton Heylin has described what he construes as the strange circumstances surrounding the song. Written around the time of Dylan's marriage to Sara Lownds, Heylin describes it as \"one of the oddest songs ever written by a man who has just tied the knot and is enjoying a brief honeymoon in the city\".<ref name = \"Heylin273\"/> Noting that the song is an elegy for a past lover, Heylin speculates that \"it is awfully tempting to see Johanna as his muse\" who, in the song, is \"not here\". For Heylin, the triumph of the song lies in \"the way Dylan manages to write about the most inchoate feelings in such a vivid, immediate way\".<ref name = \"Heylin273\"/>\n\nDylan critic [[Michael Gray (author)|Michael Gray]] also praises the subtlety of the song. Gray acknowledges that it is difficult to say what this song is \"about\", since it is at once indefinable and precise. For Gray, its principal achievement lies in the way it confuses categories, using language to be simultaneously serious and flippant, delicate and coarse, and mixing up \"abstract neo-philosophy and figurative phraseology\".<ref>{{harvnb|Gray|2000|pp=154\u2013155}}</ref>\n\nRobert Shelton called \"Visions of Johanna\" one of Dylan's major works. He writes that Dylan's technique of throwing out \"skittering images\" evokes \"a mind floating downstream\"; these \"non-sequential visions\" are the record of a fractured consciousness.<ref name=\"Shelton225\"/> Shelton argues that the song explores a hopeless quest to reach an ideal, the visions of Johanna, and yet without this quest life becomes meaningless. He suggests that the same paradox is explored by [[John Keats|Keats]] in his \"[[Ode on a Grecian Urn]]\".<ref name=\"Shelton225\"/>\n\n[[Mike Marqusee]] situates the song in New York City, \"a flickering, electric, ghostly, cityscape\".<ref name=marqusee206-207>{{harvnb|Marqusee|2005|pp=206\u2013207}}</ref> Dylan describes himself stranded in a fog of detachment which provides a haven, and at the same time is pained by a piercing clarity: an unmediated response that is \"too concise and too clear\". For Marqusee, Dylan describes his predicament, suspended between freedom and slavery, yet hungry for an authentic experience. Johanna and Louise are objects of desire and yearning. \"It is their elusiveness and unreality that's the point.\"<ref name=marqusee206-207/>\n\nGuitarist and critic [[Bill Janovitz]] also emphasizes the urban, unreal quality of \"Visions of Johanna\", calling it a \"sprawling epic\". \"The journey takes Dylan through lofts, the D train, a museum, empty lots, and through snippets of overheard conversation, as well as a discussion with some 'little boy lost', who 'takes himself so seriously', and who is 'so useless and all/muttering small talk at the wall'.\" For Janovitz, this  could \"possibly be a swipe at a critic\".<ref name=\"AllMusicJanovitz\">{{harvnb|Janovitz||}}</ref>\n\nLiterary critic [[Christopher Ricks]], in his study of Dylan's work, pinpoints the emotional effect of these same lines:\n\n::::''He\u2019s sure got a lotta gall to be so useless and all''\n::::''Muttering small talk at the wall while I\u2019m in the hall''\n\nRicks writes that the phrase \"and all\" turns a mood of helplessness into a sense of \"aggression and baffled anger\".<ref>{{harvnb|Ricks|2003|pp=487\u2013488}}</ref>\n\nTrying to unravel the mystery of the song, Greil Marcus writes that the song is concerned with internal questions, rather than external ones: \"Line by line, 'Blowin' in the Wind' is pious, or falsely innocent\u2014isn't it obvious that whoever wrote \"Yes, 'n' how many seas must a white dove sail / Before she sleeps in the sand?\" already knows the answer, assuming he, or anyone, can actually bring themselves to care about such a precious question? But 'Visions of Johanna' is asking different sorts of questions. Such as: Where are you? Who are you? What are you doing here?\" Evoking the drugged, urban milieu of the song, Marcus writes of \"People wandering from one corner of a loft to another, doped, drunk, half-awake, fast asleep, no point to the next breath, let alone the next step.\" For Marcus, \"'Visions of Johanna' makes a narrative solely out of atmosphere.\"<ref name = \"Marcus\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe song has been described by several critics as a masterpiece.<ref name = \"Heylin273\"/><ref name=\"Wilentz110\"/><ref name=\"Gill97\"/> In 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine placed the song at No.&nbsp;404 on their list of [[the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]],<ref>{{harvnb|500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2004): 401\u2013500}}</ref> commenting that Dylan \"never sounded lonelier than in this seven-minute ballad, cut in a single take on Valentine's Day 1966.\" (When ''Rolling Stone'' updated their list in 2010, the song dropped to No.&nbsp;413.)<ref>{{harvnb|500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2010): #413 \"Visions of Johanna\"}}</ref> In 1999, Britain's Poet Laureate, [[Andrew Motion]], chose it as his candidate for the best song lyric ever written. Motion praised \"the concentration and surprise\" of Dylan's lyrics, and said that, although he distanced himself from some of the singer's views about women, the \"rasp of his anger\" was a part of his greatness.<ref>{{harvnb|Thorpe|1999}}</ref> In 2017, the International Observer named the song the second best ever recorded,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.intobserver.com/the-international-observers-100-greatest-songs-of-all-time/|title=The International Observer's 100 Greatest Songs of All Time.|website=www.intobserver.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716222322/http://www.intobserver.com/the-international-observers-100-greatest-songs-of-all-time/|archive-date=2017-07-16|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-06-14}}</ref> stating, \"The 24 year old Dylan was beginning to realize that no matter how many perfect songs he wrote he could not achieve immortality through his art as he perhaps once believed, because even if people were still listening to the music in 500 years, he would still be dead.\" In an interview with ''[[The Independent]]'' in 1992, cult British musician [[Robyn Hitchcock]] described the song by saying \"it's pretty much the reason I'm a singer\".<ref>[https://durianapocalypse.net/archive/92/013092.html]</ref> Commenting on the song in a 1985 interview, Dylan said, \"I still sing that song every once in a while. It still stands up now as it did then, maybe even more in some kind of weird way.\"<ref name = \"Crowe\"/>\n\n==Cover versions==\n[[File:Grateful Dead - Jerry Garcia.jpg|thumb|Jerry Garcia recorded \"Visions of Johanna\" both as a solo artist and as a member of the Grateful Dead.]]\nThe [[Grateful Dead]] played \"Visions of Johanna\" in concert a number of times between 1986 and 1995,<ref>{{harvnb|Visions of Johanna (Dead.net)}}</ref> and both they and [[Jerry Garcia]] solo each released a live version on record.<ref>{{harvnb|Ruhlmann}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Planer: Garcia Plays Dylan}}</ref> There is also a 16-minute studio version of the song on Jerry Garcia's ''All Good Things Redux'', a bonus CD provided with the ''[[All Good Things: Jerry Garcia Studio Sessions|All Good Things]]'' box set of Garcia's studio recordings.<ref>{{harvnb|Planer: All Good Things Redux}}</ref>\n\nOther artists who have covered the song include [[Marianne Faithfull]],<ref>{{harvnb|Thompson}}</ref> [[Robyn Hitchcock]],<ref>{{harvnb|Downing}}</ref> [[Lee Ranaldo]],<ref>{{harvnb|Bush}}</ref> [[Chris Smither]],<ref>{{harvnb|Whitman}}</ref> former [[Flamin' Groovies]] guitarist [[Chris Wilson (guitarist)|Chris Wilson]],<ref>{{harvnb|Second Life: Overview}}</ref> [[Julie Felix]],<ref>{{harvnb|Julie Felix: Discography}}</ref> [[Maggie Holland]],<ref>{{harvnb|Getting There: Overview}}</ref> and [[50 Years of Blonde on Blonde|Old Crow Medicine Show]]. The jazz trio [[Michael Moore (saxophonist and clarinetist)|Jewels and Binoculars]], who named themselves after a phrase from \"Visions of Johanna\",<ref>{{harvnb|Ratliff|2008}}</ref> recorded an instrumental treatment of the song on their album ''The Music of Bob Dylan''.<ref>{{harvnb|Layne}}</ref> Foreign language versions of the song include a recording by [[Jan Erik Vold]], K\u00e5re Virud and Telemark Blueslag in Norwegian,<ref>{{harvnb|Bj\u00f6rner|2003}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stein Regn}}</ref> [[Gerard Quintana]]'s and Jordi Batiste's version in Catalan,<ref>{{harvnb|Sense reina ni as}}</ref> [[Steffen Brandt]]'s in Danish,<ref>{{harvnb|Baby Blue\u2014Bob Dylan Gendigtet: Overview}}</ref> and [[Ernst Jansz]]'s in Dutch.<ref>{{harvnb|Dromen Van Johanna}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/baby-blue-bob-dylan-gendigtet-r1711545|title=Baby Blue\u2014Bob Dylan Gendigtet: Overview|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Baby Blue\u2014Bob Dylan Gendigtet: Overview}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Olof|last=Bj\u00f6rner| authorlink=Olof  Bj\u00f6rner|url=http://www.bjorner.com/songsv.htm|title=It Ain't Me, Babe: Covers sorted by song name: V|work=Bjorner.com|date=2003-01-28|accessdate=2011-11-21|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Olof|last=Bj\u00f6rner| url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN01225%20(66).htm#_Toc476200867|title=The 6th Blonde On Blonde session, produced by Bob Johnston|work=Bjorner.com|date=2011-06-03|accessdate=2011-09-27|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=John|last=Bush|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/outlaw-blues-vol-2-r239878/review|title=Outlaw Blues, Vol. 2: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-11-20|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Al|last=Campbell|url=http://allmusic.com/album/blues-on-blonde-on-blonde-r635845/review|title=Blues on Blonde on Blonde: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite AV media notes|first=Cameron|last=Crowe|year=1985|publisher=Columbia Records|location=New York| title=Biograph|others=Bob Dylan|type=booklet|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Brian|last=Downing|url=http://allmusic.com/album/robyn-sings-r614586|title=Robyn Sings: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.ernstjansz.com/albumdromenvanjohanna.htm|title=Dromen Van Johanna|work=Ernstjansz.com|language=Dutch|accessdate=2011-10-17|ref={{SfnRef|Dromen Van Johanna}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/5|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2004): 401\u2013500|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2011-11-11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080625061023/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/5|archivedate=2008-06-22|ref={{SfnRef|500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2004): 401\u2013500}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/bob-dylan-visions-of-johanna-19691231|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2010): #413 \"Visions of Johanna\"|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2011-11-11|ref={{SfnRef|500 Greatest Songs of All Time (2010): #413 \"Visions of Johanna\"}}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106105303/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/bob-dylan-visions-of-johanna-19691231|archive-date=2011-11-06|url-status=dead}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/getting-there-r893305|title=Getting There: Overview|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Getting There: Overview}}}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Andy|last=Gill|title=Classic Bob Dylan: My Back Pages|publisher=Carlton|year=1998|isbn= 1-85868-599-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite AV media notes|first=Tony|last=Glover|year=1998|publisher=Columbia Records|location=New York| title=The Bootleg Series Vol. 4: Bob Dylan Live 1966, The \"Royal Albert Hall\" Concert|others=Bob Dylan|type=booklet|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n* {{cite AV media notes|first=Eddie|last=Gorodetsky|year=2005|publisher=Columbia Records|location=New York| title=No Direction Home: The Soundtrack\u2014The Bootleg Series Volume 7|others=Bob Dylan|type=booklet|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Michael|last=Gray|authorlink=Michael Gray (author)|title=Song & Dance Man III: The Art of Bob Dylan|publisher=Continuum International|year=2000|ref=harv|isbn=0-8264-5150-0}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Clinton|last=Heylin|title=Revolution In The Air: The Songs of Bob Dylan, Volume One: 1957\u201373 |publisher=Constable|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84901-051-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Bill|last=Janovitz|url=http://allmusic.com/song/visions-of-johanna-t1944340|title=Visions of Johanna: Song Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-11-01|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.knibbworld.com/juliefelix/records.htm|title=Julie Felix: Discography|work=Knibbworld.com|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Julie Felix: Discography}}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608142342/http://www.knibbworld.com/juliefelix/records.htm|archive-date=2012-06-08|url-status=dead}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Joslyn|last=Layne|url=http://allmusic.com/album/jewels-and-binoculars-the-music-of-bob-dylan-r565462|title=Jewels and Binoculars\u2014The Music of Bob Dylan: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Greil|last=Marcus|url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jun/21/folk.culture|title=Bob Dylan's Dream|date=2008-06-21|accessdate = 2011-11-07|work=The Guardian|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Mike|last=Marqusee|title=Wicked Messenger: Bob Dylan and the 1960s|publisher=Seven Stories Press|year=2005|isbn=978-1-58322-686-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Lindsay|last=Planer|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/all-good-things-redux-mw0001391968|title=All Good Things Redux: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2013-10-05|ref={{SfnRef|Planer: All Good Things Redux}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Lindsay|last=Planer|url=http://allmusic.com/album/garcia-plays-dylan-r796966/review|title=Garcia Plays Dylan: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Planer: Garcia Plays Dylan}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Ben|last=Ratliff| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/23/arts/music/23jewe.html| title=Dylan Without the Lyrics, Just the Melodies in Mind|work=The New York Times| date=2008-04-23|accessdate =2011-10-24|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Christopher|last=Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|publisher=Penguin/Viking|year=2003|isbn=0-670-80133-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=William|last=Ruhlmann|url=http://allmusic.com/album/fallout-from-the-phil-zone-r277543/review|title=Fallout from the Phil Zone: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/second-life-r1506417|title=Second Life: Overview|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref={{SfnRef|Second Life: Overview}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.musicaglobal.com/en/pl42/id101/discs/sense-reina-ni-as.htm|title=Sense reina ni as|work=Musicaglobal.com|language=Catalan|accessdate=2011-11-08|ref={{SfnRef|Sense reina ni as}}}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Robert|last=Shelton|title=No Direction Home: The Life and Music of Bob Dylan, Revised & updated edition |publisher=Omnibus Press|year=2011|isbn=978-1-84938-911-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.recordheaven.net/index.cfm?x=browseArtist&ID=16139&iID=81398&sc=&ob=dt&so=ASC&pp=50&pn=1&sl=false|title=Stein Regn|work=Recordheaven.net|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2011-11-21|ref={{SfnRef|Stein Regn}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Dave|last=Thompson|url=http://allmusic.com/album/rich-kid-blues-r37131|title=Rich Kid Blues: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Vanessa|last=Thorpe|url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/oct/03/vanessathorpe.theobserver1|title=Laureate gives laurels to Dylan|date=1999-10-03|accessdate = 2011-07-29|work=The Observer|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/visions-of-johanna|title=Visions of Johanna|work=Bobdylan.com|accessdate=2011-11-05|ref={{SfnRef|Visions of Johanna (Bobdylan.com)}}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111024235711/http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/visions-of-johanna|archive-date=2011-10-24|url-status=dead}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.dead.net/song/visions-johanna|title=Visions of Johanna|work=Dead.net|accessdate=2011-10-26|ref={{SfnRef|Visions of Johanna (Dead.net)}}}}\n* {{Cite web|first=Andy|last=Whitman|url=http://allmusic.com/album/leave-the-light-on-r847882|title=Leave the Light On: Review|work=Allmusic|accessdate=2011-10-16|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Sean|last=Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan In America|publisher=The Bodley Head|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84792-150-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bobdylan.com/us/songs/visions-johanna Lyrics of \"Visions of Johanna\"]\n\n{{Bob Dylan}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Bob Dylan]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bob Johnston]]\n", "name_user": "Grammarspellchecker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visions_of_Johanna"}
{"title_page": "Glen Sean Coulthard", "text_new": "{{Infobox academic|name=Glen Sean Coulthard|nationality=[[Yellowknives Dene]]|occupation=Associate Professor at [[University of British Columbia]]|known_for=[[Native American studies|First Nations and Indigenous Studies]], [[Political Science]]|education=[[University of Victoria]] (MA, PhD)|main_interests=Recognition politics, [[Indigenous sovereignty]], [[anti-colonialism]], [[Marxism]]|boards=[[Dechinta: Centre for Research and Learning]]|influences=[[Frantz Fanon]]|discipline=[[Philosophy]]|doctoral_advisor=[[James Tully (philosopher)|James Tully]]|notable_ideas=Grounded Normativity|notable_works=''Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition''|birth_date=1974}}'''Glen Sean Coulthard''' (born 1974) is a [[Yellowknives Dene First Nation|Yellowknives Dene]] associate professor in First Nations and [[Native American studies|Indigenous Studies]] and in the Department of Political Science and at the [[University of British Columbia]] (UBC). He is also a co-founder and on the board of directors at [[Dechinta: Centre for Research and Learning]].<ref name=\"Upping\">{{Cite web|url=https://uppingtheanti.org/journal/article/19-from-recognition-to-decolonization|title=From Recognition to Decolonization|website=uppingtheanti.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edgenorth.ca/article/resurgent-indigenous-politics-a-conversation-with-glen-coulthard|title=Resurgent Indigenous Politics: A Conversation With Glen Coulthard|date=2015-11-26|website=_EDGE|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Zingel|first=Avery|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/dechinta-federal-funding-1.5074493|title=Dechinta 'bush university' eyes expansion with 5 years of federal funding|date=28 March 2019|work=CBC News|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He is best known for his 2014 book, ''Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition'', which has been released in both [[English language|English]] and [[French language|French]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/41248727-red-skin-white-masks-rejecting-the-colonial-politics-of-recognition|title=Red Skin, White Masks|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.luxediteur.com/catalogue/peau-rouge-masques-blancs/|title=Peau rouge, masques blancs|website=Lux \u00c9diteur|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nCoulthard received his [[Master of Arts|Masters of Arts]] in the Indigenous Governance Program, as well as his [[Doctorate]] in [[philosophy]] in the Department of [[Political science|Political Science]], at the [[University of Victoria]].<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Facing the challenge of freedom: Dene nationalism and the politics of cultural recognition|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/facing-the-challenge-of-freedom-dene-nationalism-and-the-politics-of-cultural-recognition/oclc/858622713|date=2003|language=English|first=Glen Sean|last=Coulthard}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Coulthard|first=Glen Sean|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1828/1913|title=Subjects of Empire?: indigenous peoples and the \"Politics of recognition\" in Canada.|last2=Tully|first2=James|last3=University of Victoria (B.C.)|last4=Department of Political Science|last5=University of Victoria (B.C.)|date=2009|isbn=978-0-494-66857-3|language=English|oclc=858655508}}</ref>\n\nHis masters thesis, entitled, \"Facing the challenge of freedom : [[Dene]] nationalism and the politics of cultural recognition\", was published at the University of Victoria in 2003.\n\nHis doctorate dissertation, supervised by philosopher [[James Tully (philosopher)|James Tully]], was titled, \"Subjects of Empire? : indigenous peoples and the \"Politics of recognition\" in Canada.\", published in 2009 at the University of Victoria.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Coulthard|first=Glen Sean|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1828/1913|title=Subjects of Empire?: indigenous peoples and the \"Politics of recognition\" in Canada.|last2=Tully|first2=James|last3=University of Victoria (B.C.)|last4=Department of Political Science|last5=University of Victoria (B.C.)|date=2009|isbn=978-0-494-66857-3|language=English|oclc=858655508}}</ref> A version of this writing, entitled, \"Subjects of Empire: Indigenous Peoples and the \u2018Politics of Recognition\u2019 in Canada\", won best article of the year after being published in ''[[Contemporary Political Theory]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/8154280.Glen_Sean_Coulthard|title=Glen Sean Coulthard|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nAfter receiving his PhD at the University of Victoria in 2009, Coulthard co-founded Dechinta, with programming beginning in 2010.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dechinta.ca/past-programs|title=Past Programs|website=Dechinta|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> While he taught at Dechinta periodically, after 2015, Coulthard began spending half his teaching time there following a partnership between Dechinta and UCB.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/dechinta-partners-with-ubc-1.3325176|title=N.W.T.'s Dechinta learning centre partners with University of British Columbia|date=21 November 2015|work=CBC News|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCoulthard has visited various universities, conferences, and organizations, being featured on panels or giving lectures on topics of Indigenous politics and colonialism (see ''Recorded lectures/talks''). \n\nIn 2014, Coulthard released his first book, ''Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition'', garnering various academic awards (see ''Books'') and critical success.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://intercontinentalcry.org/book-review-red-skin-white-masks-rejecting-colonial-politics-recognition/|title=Book Review: Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition|last=Intercontinental.Cry|date=2014-08-18|website=Intercontinental Cry|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rabble.ca/blogs/bloggers/mainlander/2014/08/book-review-red-skin-white-masks-rejecting-colonial-politics-recog|title=Book review: Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition|date=2014-08-05|website=rabble.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The [[Canadian Journal of Law and Society]] said that Coulthard's book \"immediately establishes itself as a cornerstone in the areas of Indigenous governance, political theory, and activism.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Clifford|first=Robert|date=2015-08-05|title=Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition by Glen Coulthard (review)|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/588016|journal=Canadian Journal of Law and Society|language=en|volume=30|issue=2|pages=318\u2013320|issn=1911-0227}}</ref> The title itself is a play on the title of [[Frantz Fanon]]'s ''[[Black Skin, White Masks]]'', a nod to the heavy influence of Fanon's anti-colonial work that Coulthard integrated into his writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jacobinmag.com/2015/01/indigenous-left-glen-coulthard-interview|title=The Colonialism of the Present|website=jacobinmag.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> As activist and journalist [[Harsha Walia]] states, regarding ''Red Skin, White Masks'',  <blockquote>\"Coulthard's premise is a forceful one: there is no freedom to be found in or from the [[Settler colonialism|settler-colonial]] state. Drawing primarily on Frantz Fanon, Coulthard interrogates how concessions by the state maintain both the objective and subjective realms of colonial power. He challenges the [[liberal pluralism]] of state-based efforts at recognition that serve to mediate and accommodate Indigenous claims through the Canadian state itself.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rabble.ca/columnists/2015/01/land-relationship-conversation-glen-coulthard-on-indigenous-nationhood|title='Land is a Relationship': In conversation with Glen Coulthard on Indigenous nationhood|date=2015-01-20|website=rabble.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> </blockquote>''Red Skin, White Masks'' featured the Coulthard's coining of the term \"grounded normativity\", which scholar [[Leanne Betasamosake Simpson]] describes as \"the ethical frameworks generated by place-based practices and associated knowledges.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://watershedsentinel.ca/articles/nishnaabeg-anticapitalism/|title=As We Have Always Done: Nishnaabeg Anticapitalism|last=MacRae|first=Gavin|website=Watershed Sentinel|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Coulthard criticised a police-run drug prevention program for youth from the [[First Nations]] [[What\u00ec]] community, with accusations of [[poverty tourism]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Minogue|first=Sara|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/vancouver-field-trip-whati-1.5406023|title=Drug-awareness field trip to Vancouver opens eyes of N.W.T. youth, raises concerns of 'poverty tourism'|date=23 December 2019|work=CBC News|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, along with [[Angela Davis]], the Palestinian Youth Movement, [[Winona LaDuke]], and many other people and organizations, Coulthard co-signed an open letter calling on the United Nations to condemn the [[Coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]] in [[Bolivia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://progressive.org/api/content/b9ea826c-04b3-11ea-bac1-1244d5f7c7c6/|title=#ThisIsACoup|date=2019-11-11|website=Progressive.org|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nCoulthard was quoted in various publications during the early 2020 [[Timeline of the 2020 Canadian pipeline and railway protests|blockades of Canadian rail lines]] in protest of Canadian invasion of [[Wet\u02bcsuwet\u02bcen|Wet'suwet'en]] land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/news/1362716/blockades-genius-assertion-indigenous-power-ubc-based-first-nations-thinker-glen|title=Blockades a genius assertion of Indigenous power: UBC-based First Nations thinker Glen Coulthard|date=2020-02-19|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theowp.org/reports/painting-the-wetsuweten-people-by-one-stroke/|title=Painting The Wet'suwet'en People By One Stroke|website=The Organization for World Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> As quoted in [[The Guardian]], in response to backlash from [[Prime ministers of canada|Prime Minister of Canada]], [[Justin Trudeau]],<blockquote>\"He has placed the onus, the burden of proof, on Indigenous peoples to demonstrate their commitment to reconciliation on his terms \u2013 or on the terms of a weaponized majority \u2013 by pitting so-called \u2018regular Canadians and workers\u2019 against Indigenous peoples who have been rendered minorities on their homeland due to colonization and a history of genocide.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lindeman|first=Tracey|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/21/justin-trudeau-canada-rail-blockades|title=Justin Trudeau tells Canada protesters: 'The barricades need to come down'|date=2020-02-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref></blockquote>In March 2020, Coulthard wrote an open letter to [[Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness]] [[Bill Blair (politician)|Bill Blair]] in support of immigrant detainees on hunger strike in attempt to be released from Laval Immigration Monitoring Centre in [[Quebec]], due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2020/04/06/good-god-canada-migrants-are-not-criminals-release-them-all.html|title=Good God, Canada, migrants are not criminals. Release them all|date=2020-04-06|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Listed works ==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition.'' ([[Minneapolis]]: [[University of Minnesota Press]], 2014).\n** Outstanding Book, 2016 [[Caribbean Philosophical Association|Caribbean Philosophical Association\u2019s]] [[Frantz Fanon]] Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.caribbeanphilosophicalassociation.org/the-frantz-fanon-award.html|title=The Frantz Fanon Award|website=www.caribbeanphilosophicalassociation.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n** 2014/15 [[Canadian Political Science Association|Canadian Political Science Association\u2019s]] [[C. B. Macpherson|C.B. Macpherson]] Award for Best Book in [[Political theory|Political Theory]] published in English or French.\n** Rik Davidson Studies in [[Political economy|Political Economy]] 2016 Book Prize.<ref name=\"UBC Faculty page\">{{Cite web|url=https://fnis.arts.ubc.ca/persons/glen-coulthard/|title=Glen Coulthard {{!}} First Nations and Indigenous Studies|website=fnis.arts.ubc.ca|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Essays in books ===\n\n* \u201cBeyond Recognition: Indigenous Self-Determination as Prefigurative Practice.\u201d Ed. [[Leanne Betasamosake Simpson|Leanne Simpson]]. ''Lighting the Eighth Fire: The Liberation, Resurgence, and Protection of Indigenous Nations''. ([[Winnipeg]]: Arbeiter Ring Press, 2008).\n*\u201cResisting Culture: [[Seyla Benhabib|Seyla Benhabib\u2019s]] Deliberative Approach to the Politics of Recognition in Colonial Contexts.\u201d Eds. David Kahane, Dominique Leydet, Daniel Weinstock, and [[Melissa Williams]]. ''Realizing Deliberative Democracy''. ([[Vancouver]]: [[University of British Columbia Press]], 2009).\n*\u201cIndigenous Peoples and the Politics of Recognition.\u201d Ed. [[Frances Negr\u00f3n-Muntaner]]. ''Sovereign Acts''. ([[Boston]]: [[South End Press]], 2009).\n*\u201cFrom \u2018Wards of the State\u2019 to Subjects of Recognition?\u201d in [[Andrea Smith (academic)|Andrea Smith]] and Audra Simpson (eds.), ''Theorizing Native Studies'' (Durham: [[Duke University Press]], 2014).\n* \u201c#IdleNoMore in a Historical Context.\u201d Ed. The Kino-nda-niimi Collective. The Winter We Danced. ([[Winnipeg]]: ARP Books, 2014).\n\n=== Publications in journals ===\n\n* \u201cSubjects of Empire: Indigenous Peoples and the \u2018Politics of Recognition\u2019 in Canada.\u201d\u00a0 (Feature Article: Theory and Practice) ''[[Contemporary Political Theory]]'' 6:4 (2007). \n** 2007 [[Contemporary Political Theory]] Prize for Best Article of the Year.<ref name=\"UBC Faculty page\" />\n* \u201cReview: Dale Turner, ''This is Not a Peace Pipe: Towards a Critical Indigenous Philosophy.''\u201d [[University of Toronto Quarterly]] (2008).\n\n=== As editor ===\n\n* ''Indigenous Peoples and the Law.'' Book Series. Eds. Claire Charters, Glen Coulthard, Mark Harris, Denise Ferreira da Silva (New York: [[Routledge]]).\n* ''Recognition versus Self-Determination: Dilemmas of Emancipatory Politics.'' Eds. Andr\u00e9e Boisselle, Glen Coulthard, Avigail Eisenberg, and Jeremy Webber. ([[Vancouver]]: [[University of British Columbia Press]], 2014).\n*''New Socialist: Special Issue on Indigenous Resurgence.'' Issue no. 5. Eds. Gerald Taiaiake Alfred, Glen Coulthard, and Deborah Simmons.\n\n=== Recorded lectures/talks ===\n\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=usrJlFVpKaM&t=792s Recognition, Reconciliation and Resentment in Indigenous Politics, with Dr. Glen Coulthard]'' at [[Simon Fraser University]]. (November 9, 2011).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jk5XNjI2Yao Recognition, Reconciliation and Resentment in Indigenous Politics, with Dr. Glen Coulthard]'' at [[Simon Fraser University]]. (November 16, 2011).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y6NdQwJyT1U Rage Against Empire: Resentment, Reconciliation and Indigenous Decolonization in Canada]'' at the Vancouver Institute for Social Research at the [[Or Gallery]]. (February 25, 2013).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vfb7tuJxC7I First Nations & Direct Action]'' at Singing a New Song Conference in [[Canada]]. (2013).\n* ''[https://vimeo.com/110955963 \u201cRed Skin, White Masks.\u201d Unsettling Conversations, Unmaking Racisms & Colonialism]'' at [http://www.criticalracenetwork.com/ R.A.C.E. Network]\u2019s 14th Annual Critical Race and Anticolonial Studies Conference at the [[University of Alberta]]. (October 2014).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PkIUOvnA1kQ Glen Coulthard and Anwar Shaikh: The Violence of Capitalism: Race, Colonialism, & Capital]'' at Historical Materialism Toronto. (2016).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7UuhOgcyoX8 Global Movement Assemblages Symposium - Glen Coulthard]'' at the Social Justice Research Institute at [[Brock University]]. (October 2016).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9QUg5w5IeKE Global Movement Assemblages Symposium - Leanne Simpson, Rinaldo Walcott and Glen Coulthard]'' at the Social Justice Research Institute at [[Brock University]]. (October 2016).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30pf4qxOKpc Studies in Political Economy Book Prize: Glen Coulthard, Red Skin, White Masks]'' in [[Toronto]]. (May 30, 2017)\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UZE6HmN-RA0 Fanonian Antinomies]'' at [[Simon Fraser University]]. (September 25, 2017).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZslHtFie9uM Global Red Power: Fourth World Resurgent]'' in [[Auckland]]. (2018).\n\n=== Other ===\n\n* \"Facing the challenge of freedom : [[Dene]] nationalism and the politics of cultural recognition.\" Thesis. ([[University of Victoria]], 2003).\n*\"Subjects of Empire? : indigenous peoples and the \"Politics of recognition\" in Canada.\" Dissertation. ([[University of Victoria]], 2009)\n*Glen Coulthard, Mandee McDonald, Stephanie Irlbacher-Fox, and Matthew Wildcat. \"Learning from the land: Indigenous land based pedagogy and decolonization\".\n*\"Place against Empire : the Dene Nation, Land Claims, and the Politics of Recognition in the North.\" Article. ([[University of British Columbia Press]], 2014).\n*''On This Patch of Grass: City Parks on Occupied Land''. Sadie Couture, Daisy Couture, Selena Couture, [[Matt Hern]], and Erick Villagomez. Preface: Denise Ferreira da Silva. Outro: Glen Coulthard. ([[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] & [[Winnipeg]]: [[Fernwood Publishing]], 2018).\n\n*''The Fourth World: An Indian Reality''. [[George Manuel]] and [[Michael Posluns]]. Forward: [[Vine Deloria Jr.|Vine Deloria]]. Introduction: Glen Coulthard. Afterword: Doreen Manuel. ([[University of Minnesota Press|University Of Minnesota Press]], 2019).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Dene people]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Victoria alumni]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox academic|name=Glen Sean Coulthard|nationality=[[Yellowknives Dene]]|occupation=Associate Professor at [[University of British Columbia]]|known_for=[[Native American studies|First Nations and Indigenous Studies]], [[Political Science]]|education=[[University of Victoria]] (MA, PhD)|main_interests=Recognition politics, [[Indigenous sovereignty]], [[anti-colonialism]], [[Marxism]]|boards=[[Dechinta: Centre for Research and Learning]]|influences=[[Franz Fanon]]|discipline=[[Philosophy]]|doctoral_advisor=[[James Tully (philosopher)|James Tully]]|notable_ideas=Grounded Normativity|notable_works=''Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition''|birth_date=1974}}'''Glen Sean Coulthard''' (born 1974) is a [[Yellowknives Dene First Nation|Yellowknives Dene]] associate professor in First Nations and [[Native American studies|Indigenous Studies]] and in the Department of Political Science and at the [[University of British Columbia]] (UBC). He is also a co-founder and on the board of directors at [[Dechinta: Centre for Research and Learning]].<ref name=\"Upping\">{{Cite web|url=https://uppingtheanti.org/journal/article/19-from-recognition-to-decolonization|title=From Recognition to Decolonization|website=uppingtheanti.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edgenorth.ca/article/resurgent-indigenous-politics-a-conversation-with-glen-coulthard|title=Resurgent Indigenous Politics: A Conversation With Glen Coulthard|date=2015-11-26|website=_EDGE|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Zingel|first=Avery|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/dechinta-federal-funding-1.5074493|title=Dechinta 'bush university' eyes expansion with 5 years of federal funding|date=28 March 2019|work=CBC News|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He is best known for his 2014 book, ''Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition'', which has been released in both [[English language|English]] and [[French language|French]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/41248727-red-skin-white-masks-rejecting-the-colonial-politics-of-recognition|title=Red Skin, White Masks|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.luxediteur.com/catalogue/peau-rouge-masques-blancs/|title=Peau rouge, masques blancs|website=Lux \u00c9diteur|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nCoulthard received his [[Master of Arts|Masters of Arts]] in the Indigenous Governance Program, as well as his [[Doctorate]] in [[philosophy]] in the Department of [[Political science|Political Science]], at the [[University of Victoria]].<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Facing the challenge of freedom: Dene nationalism and the politics of cultural recognition|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/facing-the-challenge-of-freedom-dene-nationalism-and-the-politics-of-cultural-recognition/oclc/858622713|date=2003|language=English|first=Glen Sean|last=Coulthard}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Coulthard|first=Glen Sean|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1828/1913|title=Subjects of Empire?: indigenous peoples and the \"Politics of recognition\" in Canada.|last2=Tully|first2=James|last3=University of Victoria (B.C.)|last4=Department of Political Science|last5=University of Victoria (B.C.)|date=2009|isbn=978-0-494-66857-3|language=English|oclc=858655508}}</ref>\n\nHis masters thesis, entitled, \"Facing the challenge of freedom : [[Dene]] nationalism and the politics of cultural recognition\", was published at the University of Victoria in 2003.\n\nHis doctorate dissertation, supervised by philosopher [[James Tully (philosopher)|James Tully]], was titled, \"Subjects of Empire? : indigenous peoples and the \"Politics of recognition\" in Canada.\", published in 2009 at the University of Victoria.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Coulthard|first=Glen Sean|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1828/1913|title=Subjects of Empire?: indigenous peoples and the \"Politics of recognition\" in Canada.|last2=Tully|first2=James|last3=University of Victoria (B.C.)|last4=Department of Political Science|last5=University of Victoria (B.C.)|date=2009|isbn=978-0-494-66857-3|language=English|oclc=858655508}}</ref> A version of this writing, entitled, \"Subjects of Empire: Indigenous Peoples and the \u2018Politics of Recognition\u2019 in Canada\", won best article of the year after being published in ''[[Contemporary Political Theory]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/8154280.Glen_Sean_Coulthard|title=Glen Sean Coulthard|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nAfter receiving his PhD at the University of Victoria in 2009, Coulthard co-founded Dechinta, with programming beginning in 2010.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dechinta.ca/past-programs|title=Past Programs|website=Dechinta|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> While he taught at Dechinta periodically, after 2015, Coulthard began spending half his teaching time there following a partnership between Dechinta and UCB.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/dechinta-partners-with-ubc-1.3325176|title=N.W.T.'s Dechinta learning centre partners with University of British Columbia|date=21 November 2015|work=CBC News|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCoulthard has visited various universities, conferences, and organizations, being featured on panels or giving lectures on topics of Indigenous politics and colonialism (see ''Recorded lectures/talks''). \n\nIn 2014, Coulthard released his first book, ''Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition'', garnering various academic awards (see ''Books'') and critical success.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://intercontinentalcry.org/book-review-red-skin-white-masks-rejecting-colonial-politics-recognition/|title=Book Review: Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition|last=Intercontinental.Cry|date=2014-08-18|website=Intercontinental Cry|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rabble.ca/blogs/bloggers/mainlander/2014/08/book-review-red-skin-white-masks-rejecting-colonial-politics-recog|title=Book review: Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition|date=2014-08-05|website=rabble.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The [[Canadian Journal of Law and Society]] said that Coulthard's book \"immediately establishes itself as a cornerstone in the areas of Indigenous governance, political theory, and activism.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Clifford|first=Robert|date=2015-08-05|title=Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition by Glen Coulthard (review)|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/588016|journal=Canadian Journal of Law and Society|language=en|volume=30|issue=2|pages=318\u2013320|issn=1911-0227}}</ref> The title itself is a play on the title of [[Frantz Fanon|Franz Fanon]]'s ''[[Black Skin, White Masks]]'', a nod to the heavy influence of Fanon's anti-colonial work that Coulthard integrated into his writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jacobinmag.com/2015/01/indigenous-left-glen-coulthard-interview|title=The Colonialism of the Present|website=jacobinmag.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> As activist and journalist [[Harsha Walia]] states, regarding ''Red Skin, White Masks'',  <blockquote>\"Coulthard's premise is a forceful one: there is no freedom to be found in or from the [[Settler colonialism|settler-colonial]] state. Drawing primarily on Frantz Fanon, Coulthard interrogates how concessions by the state maintain both the objective and subjective realms of colonial power. He challenges the [[liberal pluralism]] of state-based efforts at recognition that serve to mediate and accommodate Indigenous claims through the Canadian state itself.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rabble.ca/columnists/2015/01/land-relationship-conversation-glen-coulthard-on-indigenous-nationhood|title='Land is a Relationship': In conversation with Glen Coulthard on Indigenous nationhood|date=2015-01-20|website=rabble.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> </blockquote>''Red Skin, White Masks'' featured the Coulthard's coining of the term \"grounded normativity\", which scholar [[Leanne Betasamosake Simpson]] describes as \"the ethical frameworks generated by place-based practices and associated knowledges.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://watershedsentinel.ca/articles/nishnaabeg-anticapitalism/|title=As We Have Always Done: Nishnaabeg Anticapitalism|last=MacRae|first=Gavin|website=Watershed Sentinel|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Coulthard criticised a police-run drug prevention program for youth from the [[First Nations]] [[What\u00ec]] community, with accusations of [[poverty tourism]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Minogue|first=Sara|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/vancouver-field-trip-whati-1.5406023|title=Drug-awareness field trip to Vancouver opens eyes of N.W.T. youth, raises concerns of 'poverty tourism'|date=23 December 2019|work=CBC News|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, along with [[Angela Davis]], the Palestinian Youth Movement, [[Winona LaDuke]], and many other people and organizations, Coulthard co-signed an open letter calling on the United Nations to condemn the [[Coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]] in [[Bolivia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://progressive.org/api/content/b9ea826c-04b3-11ea-bac1-1244d5f7c7c6/|title=#ThisIsACoup|date=2019-11-11|website=Progressive.org|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nCoulthard was quoted in various publications during the early 2020 [[Timeline of the 2020 Canadian pipeline and railway protests|blockades of Canadian rail lines]] in protest of Canadian invasion of [[Wet\u02bcsuwet\u02bcen|Wet'suwet'en]] land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/news/1362716/blockades-genius-assertion-indigenous-power-ubc-based-first-nations-thinker-glen|title=Blockades a genius assertion of Indigenous power: UBC-based First Nations thinker Glen Coulthard|date=2020-02-19|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theowp.org/reports/painting-the-wetsuweten-people-by-one-stroke/|title=Painting The Wet'suwet'en People By One Stroke|website=The Organization for World Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> As quoted in [[The Guardian]], in response to backlash from [[Prime ministers of canada|Prime Minister of Canada]], [[Justin Trudeau]],<blockquote>\"He has placed the onus, the burden of proof, on Indigenous peoples to demonstrate their commitment to reconciliation on his terms \u2013 or on the terms of a weaponized majority \u2013 by pitting so-called \u2018regular Canadians and workers\u2019 against Indigenous peoples who have been rendered minorities on their homeland due to colonization and a history of genocide.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lindeman|first=Tracey|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/21/justin-trudeau-canada-rail-blockades|title=Justin Trudeau tells Canada protesters: 'The barricades need to come down'|date=2020-02-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref></blockquote>In March 2020, Coulthard wrote an open letter to [[Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness]] [[Bill Blair (politician)|Bill Blair]] in support of immigrant detainees on hunger strike in attempt to be released from Laval Immigration Monitoring Centre in [[Quebec]], due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2020/04/06/good-god-canada-migrants-are-not-criminals-release-them-all.html|title=Good God, Canada, migrants are not criminals. Release them all|date=2020-04-06|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Listed works ==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''Red Skin, White Masks: Rejecting the Colonial Politics of Recognition.'' ([[Minneapolis]]: [[University of Minnesota Press]], 2014).\n** Outstanding Book, 2016 [[Caribbean Philosophical Association|Caribbean Philosophical Association\u2019s]] [[Frantz Fanon]] Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.caribbeanphilosophicalassociation.org/the-frantz-fanon-award.html|title=The Frantz Fanon Award|website=www.caribbeanphilosophicalassociation.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n** 2014/15 [[Canadian Political Science Association|Canadian Political Science Association\u2019s]] [[C. B. Macpherson|C.B. Macpherson]] Award for Best Book in [[Political theory|Political Theory]] published in English or French.\n** Rik Davidson Studies in [[Political economy|Political Economy]] 2016 Book Prize.<ref name=\"UBC Faculty page\">{{Cite web|url=https://fnis.arts.ubc.ca/persons/glen-coulthard/|title=Glen Coulthard {{!}} First Nations and Indigenous Studies|website=fnis.arts.ubc.ca|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Essays in books ===\n\n* \u201cBeyond Recognition: Indigenous Self-Determination as Prefigurative Practice.\u201d Ed. [[Leanne Betasamosake Simpson|Leanne Simpson]]. ''Lighting the Eighth Fire: The Liberation, Resurgence, and Protection of Indigenous Nations''. ([[Winnipeg]]: Arbeiter Ring Press, 2008).\n*\u201cResisting Culture: [[Seyla Benhabib|Seyla Benhabib\u2019s]] Deliberative Approach to the Politics of Recognition in Colonial Contexts.\u201d Eds. David Kahane, Dominique Leydet, Daniel Weinstock, and [[Melissa Williams]]. ''Realizing Deliberative Democracy''. ([[Vancouver]]: [[University of British Columbia Press]], 2009).\n*\u201cIndigenous Peoples and the Politics of Recognition.\u201d Ed. [[Frances Negr\u00f3n-Muntaner]]. ''Sovereign Acts''. ([[Boston]]: [[South End Press]], 2009).\n*\u201cFrom \u2018Wards of the State\u2019 to Subjects of Recognition?\u201d in [[Andrea Smith (academic)|Andrea Smith]] and Audra Simpson (eds.), ''Theorizing Native Studies'' (Durham: [[Duke University Press]], 2014).\n* \u201c#IdleNoMore in a Historical Context.\u201d Ed. The Kino-nda-niimi Collective. The Winter We Danced. ([[Winnipeg]]: ARP Books, 2014).\n\n=== Publications in journals ===\n\n* \u201cSubjects of Empire: Indigenous Peoples and the \u2018Politics of Recognition\u2019 in Canada.\u201d\u00a0 (Feature Article: Theory and Practice) ''[[Contemporary Political Theory]]'' 6:4 (2007). \n** 2007 [[Contemporary Political Theory]] Prize for Best Article of the Year.<ref name=\"UBC Faculty page\" />\n* \u201cReview: Dale Turner, ''This is Not a Peace Pipe: Towards a Critical Indigenous Philosophy.''\u201d [[University of Toronto Quarterly]] (2008).\n\n=== As editor ===\n\n* ''Indigenous Peoples and the Law.'' Book Series. Eds. Claire Charters, Glen Coulthard, Mark Harris, Denise Ferreira da Silva (New York: [[Routledge]]).\n* ''Recognition versus Self-Determination: Dilemmas of Emancipatory Politics.'' Eds. Andr\u00e9e Boisselle, Glen Coulthard, Avigail Eisenberg, and Jeremy Webber. ([[Vancouver]]: [[University of British Columbia Press]], 2014).\n*''New Socialist: Special Issue on Indigenous Resurgence.'' Issue no. 5. Eds. Gerald Taiaiake Alfred, Glen Coulthard, and Deborah Simmons.\n\n=== Recorded lectures/talks ===\n\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=usrJlFVpKaM&t=792s Recognition, Reconciliation and Resentment in Indigenous Politics, with Dr. Glen Coulthard]'' at [[Simon Fraser University]]. (November 9, 2011).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jk5XNjI2Yao Recognition, Reconciliation and Resentment in Indigenous Politics, with Dr. Glen Coulthard]'' at [[Simon Fraser University]]. (November 16, 2011).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y6NdQwJyT1U Rage Against Empire: Resentment, Reconciliation and Indigenous Decolonization in Canada]'' at the Vancouver Institute for Social Research at the [[Or Gallery]]. (February 25, 2013).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vfb7tuJxC7I First Nations & Direct Action]'' at Singing a New Song Conference in [[Canada]]. (2013).\n* ''[https://vimeo.com/110955963 \u201cRed Skin, White Masks.\u201d Unsettling Conversations, Unmaking Racisms & Colonialism]'' at [http://www.criticalracenetwork.com/ R.A.C.E. Network]\u2019s 14th Annual Critical Race and Anticolonial Studies Conference at the [[University of Alberta]]. (October 2014).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PkIUOvnA1kQ Glen Coulthard and Anwar Shaikh: The Violence of Capitalism: Race, Colonialism, & Capital]'' at Historical Materialism Toronto. (2016).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7UuhOgcyoX8 Global Movement Assemblages Symposium - Glen Coulthard]'' at the Social Justice Research Institute at [[Brock University]]. (October 2016).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9QUg5w5IeKE Global Movement Assemblages Symposium - Leanne Simpson, Rinaldo Walcott and Glen Coulthard]'' at the Social Justice Research Institute at [[Brock University]]. (October 2016).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30pf4qxOKpc Studies in Political Economy Book Prize: Glen Coulthard, Red Skin, White Masks]'' in [[Toronto]]. (May 30, 2017)\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UZE6HmN-RA0 Fanonian Antinomies]'' at [[Simon Fraser University]]. (September 25, 2017).\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZslHtFie9uM Global Red Power: Fourth World Resurgent]'' in [[Auckland]]. (2018).\n\n=== Other ===\n\n* \"Facing the challenge of freedom : [[Dene]] nationalism and the politics of cultural recognition.\" Thesis. ([[University of Victoria]], 2003).\n*\"Subjects of Empire? : indigenous peoples and the \"Politics of recognition\" in Canada.\" Dissertation. ([[University of Victoria]], 2009)\n*Glen Coulthard, Mandee McDonald, Stephanie Irlbacher-Fox, and Matthew Wildcat. \"Learning from the land: Indigenous land based pedagogy and decolonization\".\n*\"Place against Empire : the Dene Nation, Land Claims, and the Politics of Recognition in the North.\" Article. ([[University of British Columbia Press]], 2014).\n*''On This Patch of Grass: City Parks on Occupied Land''. Sadie Couture, Daisy Couture, Selena Couture, [[Matt Hern]], and Erick Villagomez. Preface: Denise Ferreira da Silva. Outro: Glen Coulthard. ([[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] & [[Winnipeg]]: [[Fernwood Publishing]], 2018).\n\n*''The Fourth World: An Indian Reality''. [[George Manuel]] and [[Michael Posluns]]. Forward: [[Vine Deloria Jr.|Vine Deloria]]. Introduction: Glen Coulthard. Afterword: Doreen Manuel. ([[University of Minnesota Press|University Of Minnesota Press]], 2019).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Dene people]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Victoria alumni]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correct name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glen_Sean_Coulthard"}
