rds\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{Queens Park Rangers F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Portsmouth F.C. Player of the Season}}\n{{Southampton F.C. Player of the Season}}\n{{Stoke City F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{100 players who shook the Kop}}\n}} \n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crouch, Peter}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Macclesfield]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Cheshire]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dulwich Hamlet F.C. players]]\n[[Category:IFK H\u00e4ssleholm players]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Norwich City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Isthmian League players]]\n[[Category:Division 1 (Swedish football) players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England B international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:People educated at Drayton Manor High School]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc}}\n{{short description|Former English association football player}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Peter Crouch\n| image          = Peter Crouch v Chelsea 2014.jpg\n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption        = Crouch playing for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in 2014\n| fullname      = Peter James Crouch<ref name=Hugman1011>{{cite book |editor-first=Barry J. |editor-last=Hugman |title=The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311 |year=2010 |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-1-84596-601-0 |page=101}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1981|1|30|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman1011/>\n| birth_place    = [[Macclesfield]], England\n| height         = {{height|ft=6|in=7}}<ref name=Hugman1011/>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub    =  \n| clubnumber     =  \n| youthyears1    = 1991\u20131993 | youthclubs1 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| youthyears2    = 1994\u20131995 | youthclubs2 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]\n| youthyears3    = 1995\u20131998 | youthclubs3 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| years1         = 1998\u20132000 | clubs1  =  [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]    | caps1  = 0   | goals1  = 0\n| years2         = 2000      | clubs2  = \u2192 [[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]] (loan)  | caps2  = 6   | goals2  = 1\n| years3         = 2000      | clubs3  = \u2192 [[IFK H\u00e4ssleholm]] (loan)                      | caps3  = 8   | goals3  = 3\n| years4         = 2000\u20132001 | clubs4  = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] | caps4  = 42  | goals4  = 10\n| years5         = 2001\u20132002 | clubs5  = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]                   | caps5  = 37  | goals5  = 18\n| years6         = 2002\u20132004 | clubs6  = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]                 | caps6  = 37  | goals6  = 6\n| years7         = 2003      | clubs7  = \u2192 [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] (loan)      | caps7  = 15  | goals7  = 4\n| years8         = 2004\u20132005 | clubs8  = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]                 | caps8  = 27  | goals8  = 12\n| years9         = 2005\u20132008 | clubs9  = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]                     | caps9  = 85  | goals9  = 22\n| years10        = 2008\u20132009 | clubs10 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]                   | caps10 = 38  | goals10 = 11\n| years11        = 2009\u20132011 | clubs11 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]     | caps11 = 73  | goals11 = 12\n| years12        = 2011\u20132019 | clubs12 = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]                   | caps12 = 225 | goals12 = 46\n| years13        = 2019      | clubs13 = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]                         | caps13 = 6   | goals13 = 0\n| totalcaps = 599 |totalgoals =\t145\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132003 | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 6  | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2006      | nationalteam2 = [[England national football B team|England B]]          | nationalcaps2 = 1  | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2005\u20132010 | nationalteam3 = [[England national football team|England]]              | nationalcaps3 = 42 | nationalgoals3 = 22\n}}\n'''Peter James Crouch'''  (born 30 January 1981) is an English former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]]. He was capped 42 times by the [[England national football team|England national team]] between 2005 and 2010, scoring 22 goals for his country in that time, and appearing at two World Cups.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2009/aug/01/peter-crouch-tottenham-expensive-english-striker|title=Are we addicted to Peter Crouch? |first=Barnay |last=Ronay |date=1 August 2009|accessdate=1 August 2009|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> Crouch is one of 28 [[List of Premier League players with 100 or more goals|players to have scored 100 or more Premier League goals]], holding the record for the most headed goals in [[Premier League records and statistics|Premier League history]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41553916 |title=Peter Crouch: Stoke striker holds Premier League record for most headers |date=9 October 2017 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nCrouch began his career as a trainee with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. He failed to make an appearance for Spurs and after loan spells at [[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]] and Swedish club [[IFK H\u00e4ssleholm]] he joined [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]. After QPR were relegated at the end of the 2000\u201301 season, [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] acquired him in a transfer deal worth \u00a31.5&nbsp;million. He had a strong first season at [[Fratton Park]], and after scoring 19 goals for the club, he joined [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in March 2002 for \u00a35&nbsp;million. He had a relatively poor spell at Villa, however, and was loaned out to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in 2003 before making a move to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], where he regained his form, which would ultimately prompt his joining [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in July 2005. At Liverpool he enjoyed considerable success, winning the [[FA Cup]] and [[FA Community Shield]] in 2006, and also gaining a runners-up medal in the [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final]].\n\nAfter scoring 42 goals in three seasons at [[Anfield]], [[Portsmouth F.C|Portsmouth]] re-acquired Crouch for \u00a311&nbsp;million, where he forged an effective partnership with fellow England international [[Jermain Defoe]]. He spent just one season in his second spell at Portsmouth and left for Tottenham Hotspur, where he again linked up with Defoe and [[Harry Redknapp]]. He scored a vital goal for Tottenham against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] which earned the club a place in the [[UEFA Champions League]]. He scored seven goals in ten European matches for Spurs in 2010\u201311, but was unable to replicate this form in the Premier League. He joined [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in August 2011, for a club record fee of \u00a310&nbsp;million. In his first season with Stoke, he scored 14 goals and won the club's [[Stoke City F.C. Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] award. He scored eight in [[2012\u201313 Stoke City F.C. season|2012\u201313]] and ten in both the [[2013\u201314 Stoke City F.C. season|2013\u201314]] and [[2014\u201315 Stoke City F.C. season|2014\u201315 seasons]]. Crouch spent seven-and-a-half years with Stoke, scoring 62 goals before joining Burnley in January 2019. He retired in July 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nCrouch was born in [[Macclesfield]], Cheshire,<ref name=Hugman1011/> but his family moved to Singapore when he was one year old.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wallace|first=Sam|title=Peter Crouch: The tall guy (and his dad) |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/peter-crouch-the-tall-guy-and-his-dad-396148.html |accessdate=4 August 2015 |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=6 October 2007 |quote=Bruce and Jayne were 21 when Peter was born and within two years the young family moved to Singapore for Bruce's work.}}</ref> His family's move to Singapore came about when his father Bruce, originally from [[Fulham]], took up a job offer to work at a Singaporean advertising agency.<ref name=\"Walking Tall\">{{cite book|last=Crouch|first=Peter|title=Walking Tall My Story|date=2007|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=9780340937129}}</ref> The Crouch family spent three years living in the Far East, and moved back to England after Bruce rejected the chance to work in Australia.<ref name=\"Walking Tall\"/> They then spent time living at a [[YMCA]] in [[Tottenham]] before settling in [[Harrow on the Hill]]. Crouch attended Roxeth Primary and [[North Ealing Primary School|North Ealing Primary]] and began to play football with Northolt Hotspurs. He was then invited to join the [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] Centre of Excellence in 1991 and he also played for the boys club West Middlesex Colts whilst attending [[Drayton Manor High School]].<ref name=\"Walking Tall\"/> Crouch turned down contract offers from [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] and instead joined [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in the summer of 1994.<ref name=\"Walking Tall\"/> He did not stay at QPR for long, however, for in November 1994, the coaching staff at [[Loftus Road]] moved to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], including its youth team manager [[Des Bulpin]], who offered Crouch a contract at Spurs.<ref name=\"Walking Tall\"/>\n\nCrouch's family were Chelsea supporters and he became a [[ball boy]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] at the age of ten.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaymirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=17173591&method=full&siteid=62484&headline=my-pete-s-no-freak-name_page.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212001904/http://www.sundaymirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid%3D17173591%26method%3Dfull%26siteid%3D62484%26headline%3Dmy-pete-s-no-freak-name_page.html |archivedate=12 December 2007 |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |first=Michael |last=Duffy |title=My Pete's No Freak |date=4 June 2006 |accessdate=4 June 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> As a child, he attended some Chelsea matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6541005.stm|title=Benitez expects test from Chelsea|publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2007 |accessdate=12 April 2007}}</ref> Later, he told the Liverpool official website that despite this, he and his friends at the time were fans of QPR.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/drilldown/N155602070413-1422.htm|title=Crouch: I Love it at Liverpool |first=Steve |last=Hunter |publisher=Liverpool F.C.|date=13 April 2007 |accessdate=13 April 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070415045541/http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/drilldown/N155602070413-1422.htm |archivedate = 15 April 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\nCrouch signed a professional contract with Tottenham Hotspur on 2 July 1998, after having played for their youth team.<ref name=\"England website\">{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersC/BioCrouchP.html |title=Peter Crouch |work=England Football Online |publisher=Glen Isherwood & Peter Young |date=24 May 2017 |accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> However, he did not make any appearances for their first team and was loaned out to other clubs, having brief spells at [[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]] in the [[Isthmian League]] Premier Division and, in the summer of 2000, [[IFK H\u00e4ssleholm]] in Sweden, where he played in the country's third tier.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/worldcup2006/story/0,,1799614,00.html|title=Mellberg says Crouch is biggest threat|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |first=Michael |last=Walker| date=17 June 2006|accessdate=18 June 2006 }}</ref> His move to Sweden came about when IFK H\u00e4ssleholm sold [[Jon J\u00f6nsson]] to Tottenham for \u00a370,000 and also agreed two loan deals for the Swedish club, that of Crouch and [[Alton Thelwell]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter Crouch: Former Tottenham Hotspur and Stoke City man in Sweden |url=http://lesrosbifs.org/peter-crouch-former-tottenham-hotspur-and-stoke-city-man-in-sweden/ |work=Les Rosbifs |accessdate=7 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610070025/http://lesrosbifs.org/peter-crouch-former-tottenham-hotspur-and-stoke-city-man-in-sweden/ |archivedate=10 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===QPR and Portsmouth===\nOn 28 July 2000, Tottenham sold Crouch to [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club Queens Park Rangers for \u00a360,000.<ref name=\"England website\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Francis grabs Grieves|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/863684.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 December 2011|date=2 August 2000}}</ref> He made an immediate impression with QPR, scoring ten league goals in the [[2000\u201301 Queens Park Rangers F.C. season|2000\u201301 season]], but it was not enough to prevent the team's relegation to the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Huddersfield 2\u20131 QPR|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/1285987.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nRelegation meant that QPR had to sell many of their best players to support their diminished finances, and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] bought Crouch for \u00a31.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Portsmouth sign \u00a31.5m Crouch|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1421884.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 December 2011|date=4 July 2001}}</ref> Crouch scored 18 [[2001\u201302 Football League|league]] goals in 37 starts for Portsmouth during the [[2001\u201302 Portsmouth F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]] and was tipped by manager [[Graham Rix]] to have a big future in the game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crouch tipped for the top|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/1650237.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 December 2011|date=11 November 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Aston Villa===\nIn March 2002, [[Premier League]] club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] made a successful \u00a35&nbsp;million bid for Crouch.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crouch seals Villa move|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1894063.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 December 2011|date=27 March 2002}}</ref> He scored on his home debut for Villa, the equalising goal against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], and went on to score twice in seven appearances.<ref>{{cite news|title=Newcastle held by Villa|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/1901022.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 December 2011|date=2 April 2002}}</ref> Crouch, however, failed to hold down a regular place in the Aston Villa team in the following [[2002\u201303 Aston Villa F.C. season|2002\u201303 season]] making 18 appearances without scoring.<ref name=sb0203/> Looking for first team football, he was loaned to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] from September to December 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canaries sign Crouch|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/3080160.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> Crouch played 15 times for the Canaries in [[2003\u201304 Norwich City F.C. season|2003\u201304]], scoring four goals helping the team gain promotion.<ref name=sb0304/> Crouch was sent off for retaliation during Norwich's 3\u20131 win at [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]], but nonetheless his spell at Norwich renewed interest in his abilities from other clubs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crouch eyes Canaries stay|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/3253998.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the three-month loan, he returned to Aston Villa, and scored a brace against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], a late winner at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and the opener at [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref name=sb0304/> Villa sold Crouch in July 2004 to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for a fee of \u00a32.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crouch joins Saints|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/southampton/3876589.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Southampton===\nDespite initially being back-up to first choice strikers [[James Beattie (footballer)|James Beattie]] and [[Kevin Phillips (footballer)|Kevin Phillips]], Crouch became the main attacking focus of the Southampton team upon the arrival of [[Harry Redknapp]] and the sale of Beattie.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beattie to complete \u00a36.5m Everton switch|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2353206/Beattie-to-complete-6.5m-Everton-switch.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=30 May 2017|date=3 January 2005}}</ref> He scored many key goals in Southampton's relegation battle, including memorable goals against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in a 2\u20130 home win, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in a 1\u20131 home draw and two away to Middlesbrough in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Middlesbrough 1\u20133 Southampton|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4343227.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=20 March 2005}}</ref> He also scored a late winning penalty to knock former club and [[South Coast derby|Saints' arch-rival]] Portsmouth out of the [[2004\u201305 FA Cup|FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Southampton 2\u20131 Portsmouth|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/4197721.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=29 January 2005}}</ref> His form for the Saints eventually resulted in him receiving his first [[England national football team|England]] call-up.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Cup Scouting \u2013 Peter Crouch|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/teams/england/4750849.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> After scoring 16 goals in 33 appearances during the [[2004\u201305 Southampton F.C. season|2004\u201305 season]], his future was cast into doubt when Southampton were relegated from the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|title=Southampton 1\u20132 Man Utd|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4525113.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=15 May 2005}}</ref> On 19 July 2005, Southampton agreed to sell Crouch for \u00a37&nbsp;million to Liverpool on a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crouch completes Liverpool move|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4677639.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 June 2013|date=20 July 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Liverpool===\n[[File:Peter Crouch 2006.jpg|thumb|upright|Crouch with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2006]]\n\nCrouch underwent intense media scrutiny because of a goal drought during his first months at Liverpool. For 19 matches\u2014the span of four months\u2014he was unable to score. Crouch was praised for other facets of his game, such as his touch on the ball, but his first goal for the club evaded him. The fact that Crouch possessed \"good touch for a big man\" became something of a media [[clich\u00e9]] during this time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,1588933,00.html|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |first=Barry|last=Glendenning|title=The Crouch-a-saurus|date=10 October 2005 |accessdate=4 June 2006 }}</ref> Early in his Liverpool career, the supporters composed a new chant: \"He's big, he's red, his feet stick out the bed, Peter Crouch, Peter Crouch.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The long and the short of it|url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/review/story/0,,2042066,00.html|first=Simon|last=Garfield |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |date=25 March 2007 |accessdate=6 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe drought finally ended on 3 December 2005 when he scored against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]. Although this first goal was originally given as an [[own goal]], it was later awarded to Crouch on appeal; he went on to score a second goal in the same match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4473084.stm|title=Liverpool 3\u20130 Wigan |date=3 December 2005 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref> Before these goals, Crouch had played over 24 hours of football for Liverpool without scoring. In addition to this, he also had to deal with unpleasant taunts from crowds at matches, as he had throughout his footballing career, who often chanted \"[[freak]]\" at him due to his unusual height.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/worldcup2006/story/0,,1782536,00.html|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London | first=Daniel| last=Taylor| title=Crouch rises above the jibes to feel at home among the elite|date=25 May 2006 |accessdate=4 June 2006 }}</ref> He went on to score several goals that season, including the only goal in the fifth round of the [[FA Cup]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], Liverpool's first victory over them in the FA Cup post-Second World War.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/4720494.stm|title=Liverpool 1\u20130 Man Utd |date=18 February 2006 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref> On 13 May, he helped Liverpool to win the [[2006 FA Cup Final]] against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], providing an assist for [[Steven Gerrard]] to score the second Liverpool goal.<ref name=2006FAC>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/4756045.stm |title=Liverpool 3\u20133 West Ham (aet) |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 May 2006 |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Peter Crouch.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Crouch warming up for Liverpool in 2007]]\n\nThree months later, in the curtain-raiser to the [[2006\u201307 Liverpool F.C. season|2006\u201307 season]], he headed the winning goal for Liverpool in the club's 2\u20131 victory over Chelsea in the [[FA Community Shield]].<ref name=2006FACS>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4780739.stm |title=Chelsea 1\u20132 Liverpool |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 August 2006 |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref> In their [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League]] campaign, he scored his first goals in European club competition against [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.|Maccabi Haifa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Maccabi H 1\u20131 Liverpool (agg 2\u20133)|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/5266050.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=22 August 2006}}</ref> Crouch sustained a [[nasal fracture|broken nose]] when playing against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in February 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6394923.stm|title=Liverpool star Crouch breaks nose|publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 February 2007|accessdate=9 March 2007}}</ref> Although he played in some subsequent matches, on 9 March 2007, it was announced that he would undergo surgery on the injury that would keep him out of football for a month.<ref>{{cite news|title=Broken nose for Crouch|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/2406576/broken-nose-for-crouch|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> On 31 March, he returned to action after the operation and scored the first [[hat-trick]] of his club career, coming against Arsenal in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6491075.stm|title=Liverpool 4\u20131 Arsenal|publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2007|accessdate=31 March 2007|first=Phil|last=McNulty}}</ref> This was also a so-called \"[[Hat-trick#Association football|perfect hat-trick]],\" consisting of goals scored from his right foot, left foot and head.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.setanta.com/portal/article/motorsports?open&articleid=4295990dcaecea6b802572ae005ec839 |title=Crouch hat-trick sees off poor Arsenal|publisher=Setanta Sports|date=31 March 2007 |accessdate=31 March 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930155156/http://au.setanta.com/portal/article/motorsports?open&articleid=4295990dcaecea6b802572ae005ec839 |archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref> He later participated in the [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final]], coming on as a substitute for [[Javier Mascherano]] as Liverpool were defeated by [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in Athens.<ref name=2007UCL>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6669039.stm |title=AC Milan 2\u20131 Liverpool |first=Phil |last=McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 May 2007 |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref> He ended the 2006\u201307 season as Liverpool's top goalscorer in all competitions, with eighteen goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/SeasonArchive/Goalscorers/116|title= Liverpool Top Goalscorers 2006\u20132007 Season|publisher=LFCHistory.net|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of the [[2007\u201308 Liverpool F.C. season|2007\u201308 season]], he had restricted opportunities to play for Liverpool due to the arrival of other strikers, including [[Fernando Torres]], but nonetheless scored against [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]] in a [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] qualifying win in August, his eighth goal in his past ten appearances in that competition,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/Match_Report/0,,2158021,00.html|title=Frustrated Crouch helps Liverpool cruise through|first=Andy|last=Hunter|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=29 August 2007|accessdate=1 September 2007 }}</ref> and then also scoring the first and last goals of an 8\u20130 win over [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] in the first round of the Champions League in November.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7076592.stm|title= Liverpool 8\u20130 Besiktas |date=6 November 2007 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=15 July 2009|first=Mandeep|last=Sanghera}}</ref> On 19 December, Crouch was sent off in the quarter-finals of the League Cup, receiving a straight red card for a foul on Chelsea's [[John Obi Mikel]] as Liverpool exited the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sanghera|first=Mandeep|title=Chelsea 2\u20130 Liverpool|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/7145789.stm|accessdate=30 October 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 December 2007}}</ref> In April, he scored a vital goal in a 1\u20131 draw against Arsenal, helping Liverpool secure fourth spot ahead of [[Merseyside derby|local rivals]] [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Arsenal 1\u20131 Liverpool|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7320164.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=5 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Portsmouth===\n[[File:Portsmouth kickoff vs AC Milan.jpg|thumb|upright|Crouch playing for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in 2008]]\n\nOn 7 July 2008, it was announced that Crouch had verbally agreed to join former club and FA Cup holders Portsmouth in a deal worth up to \u00a311&nbsp;million. Crouch passed his medical the following day,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7471969.stm |title=Crouch passes Portsmouth medical |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2008 |accessdate=9 July 2008}}</ref> and, on 11 July, Crouch's transfer was officially unveiled at a Portsmouth news conference.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/7471969.stm |title=Portsmouth set to unveil Crouch |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2008  |accessdate=8 July 2008}}</ref> Crouch scored his first goal on his return to Portsmouth in a 3\u20130 win against Everton at [[Goodison Park]] on 30 August 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/7578439.stm|title=Everton 0\u20133 Portsmouth |date=30 August 2008 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 July 2009|first=Phil|last=McNulty}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Crouch credited with Goodison goal|url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/sport/football/pompey/crouch-credited-with-goodison-goal-1-1301238|newspaper=The News |location=Portsmouth |accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> Crouch then went on to net his first goal at Portsmouth's [[Fratton Park]] home ground in the Premier League against Tottenham Hotspur on 28 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/?cms_id=78&qs_articleid=1501&qs_media=html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006062226/http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/?cms_id=78&qs_articleid=1501&qs_media=html |url-status=dead |archivedate=6 October 2008 |title=Crouch credited with third at Everton |publisher=Portsmouth F.C. |date=3 September 2008 | accessdate=4 September 2008}}</ref> On 2 October 2008, Crouch scored twice in extra time in a [[UEFA Cup]] match away to Portuguese team [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]] to help Portsmouth reach the group stages of [[2008\u201309 UEFA Cup|the competition]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7639445.stm|title=Guimaraes 2\u20132 Portsmouth (2\u20134)  |publisher=BBC  |date=2 October 2008 | accessdate=3 October 2008 |first=Sam |last=Lyon}}</ref> He went on to score twice against [[SC Heerenveen|Heerenveen]] in a 3\u20130 victory at Fratton Park, however Portsmouth failed to make it out of the group stages.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7775400.stm|title=Portsmouth 3\u20130 Heerenveen |date=18 December 2008 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=15 July 2009}}</ref> Crouch played 46 times for Pompey in [[2008\u201309 Portsmouth F.C. season|2008\u201309]], scoring 16 goals as the side finished in 14th position.<ref name=sb0809/>\n\n===Return to Tottenham Hotspur===\n[[File:Peter Crouch Andrew Johnson.jpg|thumb|upright|Crouch playing for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in 2011]]\n\nOn 27 July 2009, Tottenham Hotspur signed Crouch from Portsmouth for a fee of \u00a310&nbsp;million, on a five-year contract.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8169170.stm | title=Tottenham complete Crouch signing |publisher=BBC Sport  | date=27 July 2009| accessdate=27 July 2009 }}</ref> Crouch made his debut for Spurs in a pre-season friendly against [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Ley |first=John |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/6003264/Peter-Crouch-upbeat-after-Tottenham-debut.html |title=Peter Crouch upbeat after Tottenham debut |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=10 August 2009 |accessdate=30 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108201035/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/6003264/Peter-Crouch-upbeat-after-Tottenham-debut.html |archivedate=8 January 2014 }}</ref> and came on as a substitute in Tottenham's season opening win over Liverpool, making his full Premier League debut for the club in the process.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8198253.stm |title=Tottenham 2\u20131 Liverpool |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 August 2009 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Tottenham in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]] in a 5\u20131 win on 26 August 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8214938.stm|title=Doncaster 1\u20135 Tottenham|publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 August 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2009}}</ref> He scored again in his next match, opening his league account with Spurs with a goal in a 2\u20131 home win against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8224017.stm |title=Tottenham 2\u20131 Birmingham |date=29 August 2009 |accessdate=5 September 2009 |first=Sam |last=Lyon |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 23 September, Crouch scored his first hat-trick for Spurs in a 5\u20131 win over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in the [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fletcher |first=Paul |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8257298.stm |title=Preston 1\u20135 Tottenham |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 September 2009 |accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=sb0910/> In May, his late goal against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in what was being dubbed as the \"\u00a315&nbsp;million pound game\" put Spurs in a position to claim their first-ever Champions League berth. After having hit the post and missed a [[Beno\u00eet Assou-Ekotto]] cross, Crouch scored a header after goalkeeper [[M\u00e1rton F\u00fcl\u00f6p]] could only parry the ball into his path.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8659403.stm|title=Tottenham reach Champions League (Man City 0\u20131 Tottenham)|last=McNulty  |first=Phil|date=5 May 2010|publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 August 2010, Crouch scored a hat-trick at [[White Hart Lane]] against [[BSC Young Boys|Young Boys]] to help Tottenham to reach the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]] of the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|2010\u201311 Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Tottenham 4\u20130 Young Boys (agg 6\u20133)|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8939577.stm|first=Mandeep|last= Sanghera|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=25 August 2010|date=25 August 2010}}</ref> On 15 February 2011, Crouch scored what turned out to be the winning goal in the Champions League second round, first leg match against Milan at the [[San Siro]], sweeping home [[Aaron Lennon]]'s cut-back after a counter-attack.<ref>{{cite news|title=AC Milan 0\u20131 Tottenham |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/9396732.stm|date=15 February 2011 |accessdate=6 April 2011|first=Mandeep|last= Sanghera|publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref> Three weeks later, Spurs progressed to the quarter-finals after the reverse fixture at White Hart Lane ended 0\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tottenham 0\u20130 AC Milan (agg 1\u20130) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9417468.stm|date=9 March 2011 |accessdate=6 April 2011|first=Phil|last= McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref> On 5 April, he was sent off in the 14th minute after receiving two yellow cards in the quarter-finals against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Real Madrid 4\u20130 Tottenham |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/9445378.stm|date=5 April 2011|accessdate=5 April 2011|first=Marc |last=Vesty |publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref> He scored an own goal against Manchester City, which consequently confirmed City into the Champions League for the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League|2011\u201312 season]] with Tottenham finishing fifth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man City 1\u20130 Tottenham|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9480251.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 June 2013|date=10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Stoke City===\n[[File:Crouch2.jpg|thumb|upright|Crouch warming up for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in 2012]]\n\nOn 31 August 2011, [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] signed Crouch from Tottenham for a then club record fee of \u00a310&nbsp;million, that would rise to \u00a312&nbsp;million, on a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stokecityfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10310~2438170,00.html |title=Crouch Seals Club Record Transfer |publisher=Stoke City F.C. |date=31 August 2011 |accessdate=31 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027182236/http://www.stokecityfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10310~2438170%2C00.html |archivedate=27 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14729457.stm|title=Stoke City sign Tottenham Hotspur's Peter Crouch in \u00a312m deal|publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 August 2011|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref> Speaking after sealing his move to the [[bet365 Stadium|Britannia Stadium]], Crouch revealed that his former Tottenham teammate [[Jonathan Woodgate]] was a major influence upon his decision to join Stoke.<ref>{{cite news|title=Woodgate backs Crouch for England duty|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Stoke-City-Woodgate-backs-Crouch-England-duty/story-13259445-detail/story.html|newspaper=The Sentinel|location=Stoke-on-Trent|accessdate=5 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222231508/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Woodgate-backs-Crouch-England-duty/story-13259445-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref> Crouch made his debut for Stoke City in a 1\u20130 win against former club Liverpool on 10 September 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stokecityfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10310~2446655,00.html |title=Crouch Handed Potters Debut |publisher=Stoke City F.C. |date=11 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020110750/http://www.stokecityfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10310~2446655%2C00.html |archivedate=20 October 2011}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the Potters in a 1\u20131 draw against Manchester United, making Stoke the sixth Premier League club he has scored for.<ref>{{cite news |last=Da Silva |first=Michael |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14958150.stm|title=Stoke 1\u20131 Man Utd |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 September 2011 |accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref> He scored his second goal in the following match against Be\u015fikta\u015f in the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15014644.stm |title=Stoke 2\u20131 Besiktas |last=Rostance |first=Tom |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 October 2011 |accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref> Crouch went on to score against Arsenal, [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]], [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] before missing out on the Christmas period matches after suffering from a virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Crouch struck down by virus |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Stoke-City-Crouch-struck-virus/story-14251398-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505103854/http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Stoke-City-Crouch-struck-virus/story-14251398-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |newspaper=The Sentinel |location=Stoke-on-Trent |date=27 September 2011 |accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 January 2012, against Blackburn, Crouch scored both goals in a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Blackburn 1\u20132 Stoke |last=Sheringham |first=Sam |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16331068.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 January 2012|date=2 January 2012}}</ref> It was a landmark achievement for Crouch as he surpassed 100 league goals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Peter Crouch 'proud' to reach 100 league goals |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16386723.stm? |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 January 2012 |date=2 January 2012}}</ref> On 24 March 2012, Crouch scored a stunning long-distance volley against Manchester City in a 1\u20131 draw at the Britannia Stadium.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stoke 1\u20131 Manchester City |last=Lillywhite |first=Jamie |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/17412553 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 March 2012 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> After the match, Crouch stated that it was the best goal of his career.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stoke striker Peter Crouch joy at 'best' career goal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/17505110? |publisher=BBC Sport |date = 25 March 2012 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> He scored the winning goal for Stoke against their Midlands rivals Wolves on 7 April to take his goal tally to 13 and was backed by manager [[Tony Pulis]] to earn a recall to the England squad for [[UEFA Euro 2012]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Pulis Backs Crouch's Euro Bid |url=http://www.stokecityfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10310~2727551,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409202428/http://www.stokecityfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10310~2727551%2C00.html |archivedate= 9 April 2012 |publisher=Stoke City F.C. |accessdate=8 April 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> At the end of season awards dinner, Crouch won the club's [[Stoke City F.C. Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and Goal of the Season awards.<ref name=stokeawards>{{cite news |title=Stoke City: Peter Crouch scoops player-of-the-year award |url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-scoops-player-year-award/story-16032040-detail/story.html |newspaper=The Sentinel |location=Stoke-on-Trent |date=9 May 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702082924/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-scoops-player-year-award/story-16032040-detail/story.html |archivedate=2 July 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCrouch began the [[2012\u201313 Stoke City F.C. season|2012\u201313 season]] well, scoring five goals in seven matches, against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]], Wigan Athletic, Manchester City and a brace against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Stoke 2\u20130 Swansea |last = Roberts |first = Simon |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/19684209|publisher=BBC Sport| date = 29 September 2012 |accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Crouch not thinking of England |url=http://www.football.co.uk/stoke_city/crouch_not_thinking_of_england_rss3563018.shtml|publisher=football.co.uk|date=1 October 2012| accessdate= 30 September 2014}}</ref> He lost several teeth after being accidentally kicked in the mouth by [[Fabricio Coloccini]] in a match against Newcastle United on 28 November 2012 and as a result had to undergo corrective surgery.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stoke City: Peter Crouch still struggling after mouth injury, Tony Pulis reveals |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-struggling-mouth-injury/story-17903228-detail/story.html |accessdate=22 March 2013 |newspaper=The Sentinel |location=Stoke-on-Trent |date=19 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226045019/http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-struggling-mouth-injury/story-17903228-detail/story.html |archivedate=26 February 2013  }}</ref> He then went three months without a goal before scoring against Wigan on 29 January 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Gary|title=Stoke 2\u20132 Wigan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21137488|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 January 2013|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> Crouch again went through a three-month barren spell in front of goal before scoring against former club Queens Park Rangers on 20 April 2013 in a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Sheringham |title=QPR 0\u20132 Stoke|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22133477|publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2013 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> He scored on the final day of the season against Southampton as he ended the 2012\u201313 season with eight goals, with Stoke finishing 13th in the league.<ref name=sb1213/>\n\n[[Mark Hughes]] replaced Tony Pulis as manager in May 2013 and despite starting the first two matches of the [[2013\u201314 Stoke City F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]], Hughes dropped Crouch to the bench.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peter Crouch ready to make Potters impact|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-ready-make-Potters-impact/story-19985694-detail/story.html|newspaper=The Sentinel|location=Stoke-on-Trent|accessdate=25 October 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193426/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-ready-make-Potters-impact/story-19985694-detail/story.html|archivedate=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ian |last=Edwards |title=Hughes plays down Crouch speculation |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/english-premier-league/story/1594400/stoke-boss-mark-hughes-plays-down-peter-crouch-speculation |publisher=ESPN |date=25 October 2013 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> He returned to the starting line up on 26 October 2013 and scored in a 3\u20132 defeat against Manchester United.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Bevan |title=Manchester United 3\u20132 Stoke City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24591160 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 October 2013 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> Crouch retained his place in the team for the remainder of the 2013\u201314 season, where he finished as top scorer with ten goals in 38 appearances as Stoke finished in ninth place.<ref name=sb1314/>\n\nCrouch scored his first goals of [[2014\u201315 Stoke City F.C. season|2014\u201315]] in September 2014 against QPR and Newcastle.<ref>{{cite news |first=Aimee |last=Lewis |title=Queens Park Rangers 2\u20132 Stoke City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29187276 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 September 2014 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Graham |last=Chase |title=Stoke City 1\u20130 Newcastle United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29305924 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 September 2014 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> In October 2014, Crouch stated that he would like to remain at the Britannia Stadium with Stoke for the remainder of his career.<ref>{{cite news |title=Peter Crouch: Stoke City's record signing ready to commit future |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29627695 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> On 29 October 2014, Crouch came on as a substitute in Stoke's League Cup defeat to Southampton; 15 minutes later, he was sent off for two yellow cards in the space of two minutes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stoke City 2\u20133 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29718448 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 October 2014 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> On 6 December, he scored after 19 seconds against Arsenal in an eventual 3\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chowdhury |first=Saj |title=Stoke City 3\u20132 Arsenal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30257121 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 December 2014 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> A week later, in his 600th match in English football, Crouch scored the equaliser in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McLeman|first=Neil|title=Crystal Palace 1\u20131 Stoke City match report: Peter Crouch frustrates Eagles to earn Potters a point|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/crystal-palace-stoke-match-report-4804703|accessdate=14 December 2014|newspaper=Daily Mirror|location=London|date=13 December 2014}}</ref> Crouch signed a two-year contract extension in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Key duo extend their stay|url=http://www.stokecityfc.com/news/article/exclusive-key-duo-extend-their-stay-2234299.aspx|publisher=Stoke City F.C.|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 2015, Crouch scored the winning goal in Stoke's 1\u20130 win over [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], equaling [[Alan Shearer]]'s record of 46 headed goals in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Stone |title=Stoke City 1\u20130 Hull City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31562895 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 February 2015 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> He surpassed this on 24 May with a header five minutes after coming on as a substitute to conclude a 6\u20131 home win over Liverpool in Stoke's final match of the season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnston|first=Neil|title=Stoke 6\u20131 Liverpool|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32770765|accessdate=24 May 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 May 2015}}</ref> In total, Crouch matched the previous season's goal tally of ten goals in 38 appearances as Stoke finished in ninth position for the second consecutive season.<ref name=sb1415/> Following the end of the season, Crouch underwent groin surgery.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peter Crouch goes under the knife to resolve groin problem|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-goes-knife-resolve-groin/story-26582530-detail/story.html?|newspaper=The Sentinel|location=Stoke-on-Trent|accessdate=27 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528015914/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-goes-knife-resolve-groin/story-26582530-detail/story.html|archivedate=28 May 2015}}</ref> Crouch struggled for game time in [[2015\u201316 Stoke City F.C. season|2015\u201316]] making 18 appearances of which nine were as a substitute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peter Crouch still has big role to play insists Mark Hughes|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Peter-Crouch-big-role-play-insists/story-29206050-detail/story.html|newspaper=The Sentinel|location=Stoke-on-Trent|accessdate=24 May 2016}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He scored just twice, which came against lower league [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and Doncaster Rovers in cup competitions.<ref name=sb1516/>\n\nCrouch scored a hat-trick away to [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] in the [[2016\u201317 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]], on 23 August 2016 in a 4\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37091171|title=Stevenage 0 Stoke 4|date=23 August 2016|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> On 9 January 2017, Crouch signed a new contract with Stoke in a deal lasting until the summer of 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stokecityfc.com/news/article/2016-17/peter-crouch-new-contract-2018-3510509.aspx|title=Exclusive: Crouch Signs New Deal|date=9 January 2017|publisher=Stoke City F.C.|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38560353|title=Peter Crouch: Stoke City striker signs new deal with Potters|date=9 January 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> Crouch scored four goals in five games at the turn of the year including his [[List of Premier League players with 100 or more goals|100th Premier League goal]], the oldest player to hit the landmark.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke 1\u20131 Everton|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38740422|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38560353|title=Peter Crouch just became the oldest player in Premier League history to reach 100 goals|date=1 February 2017|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref> Crouch made 29 appearances in [[2016\u201317 Stoke City F.C. season|2016\u201317]], scoring ten goals, as Stoke finished in 13th position.<ref name=sb1617/> After the season ended Crouch stated that he wants to continue playing until he is 40.<ref>{{cite news|title=The secret of my longevity by Stoke City evergreen Peter Crouch|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/the-secret-of-my-longevity-by-stoke-city-evergreen-peter-crouch/story-30359613-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530105009/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/the-secret-of-my-longevity-by-stoke-city-evergreen-peter-crouch/story-30359613-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 May 2017|newspaper=The Sentinel|location=Stoke-on-Trent|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nCrouch set a record for the most number of appearances as substitute in the Premier League, on 20 November 2017 when he came off the bench for the 143rd time against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], breaking the record held by [[Shola Ameobi]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Tom |last=White |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/peter-crouch-sets-premier-league-record-for-substitute-appearances-a3696781.html |title=Peter Crouch sets Premier League record for substitute appearances |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=20 November 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stoke's Peter Crouch breaks Premier League record for substitute appearances |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/stoke-city/story/3277835/stokes-peter-crouch-breaks-premier-league-record-for-substitute-appearances |publisher=ESPN |date=20 November 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> He also became Stoke City's leading Premier League goalscorer of all time during the same season, reaching 45 goals and overtaking the 43 scored by [[Jonathan Walters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statbunker.com/alltimestats/AllTimeLeadingScorers?comp_code=EPL&club_id=187|title=Premier League Stoke City All time - Leading Scorers|website=Statbunker|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> Crouch signed another one-year contract extension with the Potters in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Peter Crouch: Stoke striker extends stay with new deal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42151947 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 November 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> Crouch played 34 times in [[2017\u201318 Stoke City F.C. season|2017\u201318]], scoring six goals as Stoke were relegated to the [[EFL Championship|Championship]].<ref name=sb1718/>\n\n===Burnley===\nCrouch signed for Premier League club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 31 January 2019 on a contract until the end of the [[2018\u201319 Burnley F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]] in a player-exchange deal with [[Sam Vokes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47070349 |title=Peter Crouch: Stoke City striker signs for Burnley with Sam Vokes moving to Potters |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 January 2019 |accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref> Crouch made his debut for [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 2 February, coming on as a 76th minute substitute in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]; he made an immediate impact, as he was instrumental in Burnley being awarded their first penalty for a season-and-a-half.<ref>{{Cite web|first = Matthew |last= Howarth |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47011452|publisher = BBC Sport |title=Burnley 1\u20131 Southampton: Ashley Barnes penalty rescues point for hosts|date=2 February 2019|access-date=4 February 2019}}</ref> He was released at the end of the season<ref>{{cite web |title=2018/19 Premier League clubs' released lists |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1238381?sf213988963=1 |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref> and announced his retirement from professional football on 12 July 2019 at the age of 38.<ref>{{cite web |title=Peter Crouch retires|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48964162 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=12 July 2019|date=12 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth international===\nCrouch was capped for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20 team]] at the [[1999 FIFA World Youth Championship]], with teammates including [[Stuart Taylor (footballer, born 1980)|Stuart Taylor]], [[Ashley Cole]], [[Andrew Johnson (English footballer)|Andrew Johnson]] and [[Matthew Etherington]]. However, the team finished bottom at the group stage, with three losses and having scored no goals.<ref>{{cite web|title=FIFA World Youth Championship Nigeria 1999|url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/archive/nigeria1999/teams/team=1888255/index.html|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> He was later a part of [[David Platt (footballer)|David Platt]]'s [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 team]], which went to the finals of the [[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|European Under-21 Championship]] in Switzerland in May 2002, where he scored once against [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite news|title=England see off Swiss|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1991611.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 December 2011|date=17 May 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Crouch's giant stride|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1995674.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 December 2011|date=18 May 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Breakthrough into senior team===\nIn May 2005 he was handed his first call-up to the England senior squad by manager [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] for the team's tour of the United States, making his debut against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,1563,1532543,00.html|title=Crouch 'thrilled' at Anfield move|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=20 July 2005|accessdate=26 January 2007 }}</ref> He went on to make two appearances during the [[Football World Cup 2006 (qualification UEFA)|2006 FIFA World Cup qualifying campaign]] for England: starting against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in a 1\u20130 victory and coming on as a substitute against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] in a 2\u20131 win. In the latter appearance, Crouch's introduction as a second-half substitute was booed by England's own supporters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4337334.stm|title=Cole condemns fans' Crouch abuse|publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 October 2005|accessdate=26 January 2007}}</ref> On 1 March 2006, he scored his first goal for England, with the equaliser in a 2\u20131 friendly win over [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=England players hail hero Crouch |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4765070.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 March 2006 |accessdate=26 January 2007}}</ref> He did this whilst bizarrely wearing two different [[squad number]]s on his shirt \u2013 No.&nbsp;21 on the front (his designated squad number for the match), and the incorrect No.&nbsp;12 on the back.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/news/matchreport/0,,1721075,00.html|title=England 2\u20131 Uruguay|first=Mike|last=Adamson|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=1 March 2006|accessdate=26 January 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2006, Crouch was included in the 23-man England squad for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], and was expected to be a significant figure in the team due to [[Wayne Rooney]]'s foot injury.<ref>{{cite web|title=Walcott & Lennon in England squad|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/teams/england/4983618.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=8 May 2006}}</ref> On 30 May, he played in a pre-[[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] friendly against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], scoring the third goal in England's 3\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite web|title=England 3\u20131 Hungary|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/teams/england/5029634.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=30 May 2006}}</ref> He followed his goal with his iconic [[robot (dance)|robotic dancing]] [[goal celebration]].<ref>{{cite news |title=C'mon everybody ... Let's do the Crouch!|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jun/01/sport.comment2|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> On 3 June, he scored a hat-trick in a 6\u20130 pre-World Cup friendly victory against [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] where he again performed his robotic celebration.<ref>{{cite web|title=PETER CROUCH'S ENGLAND TREBLE SPARKS ROBOTIC CELEBRATIONS|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2015/jun/02/peter-crouch-robot-jamaica|publisher=The Football Association |accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2006 World Cup===\n[[File:England team.jpg|thumb|right|Crouch (wearing No.21) lining up for [[England national football team|England]] against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]]]\n\nAfter his displays in England's friendlies, Crouch partnered with [[Michael Owen]] in attack for England's opening 2006 World Cup match against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] on 10 June 2006. England won the match 1\u20130 and Crouch kept his place in the starting line-up for the following match against [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]], against whom he scored his first competitive international goal. The goal provoked some controversy as replays showed Crouch to be pulling on [[Brent Sancho]]'s long hair, holding the defender down, to gain an advantage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sport.scotsman.com/football.cfm?id=888922006|newspaper=The Scotsman |location=Edinburgh |title=Sancho angry as TV shows Crouch pulled hair to climb |first=Colin |last=Stewart |date=17 June 2006 |accessdate=17 June 2006}}</ref>\n\nCrouch was rested for England's third group match against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] as Rooney returned from injury to join the starting line-up. However, Owen suffered a serious knee injury in the opening minute of the match and Crouch replaced him, playing the remainder of the match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden 2\u20132 England|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853282.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=20 June 2006}}</ref> In England's 1\u20130 second round victory against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]], Crouch remained an unused substitute as Eriksson switched the team to a new formation with Wayne Rooney as a lone striker.<ref>{{cite web|title=England 1\u20130 Ecuador|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991536.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=25 June 2006}}</ref> After Rooney's dismissal for a foul in England's quarter-final against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], Crouch came on as a substitute for [[Joe Cole]], as England went on to get knocked out on penalties.<ref>{{cite web|title=England 0\u20130 Portugal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991618.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=1 July 2006}}</ref> On 5 September 2007, retired English referee [[Graham Poll]] claimed that [[FIFA]] had specifically warned referees at the event to pay close attention to Crouch, claiming that \"he's a real pain and he's getting away with too much.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,2162757,00.html|title=Poll says Crouch is targeted by referees|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=5 September 2007 |accessdate=5 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Euro 2008 qualifying===\nCrouch remained a part of the England set-up under Eriksson's successor as manager, [[Steve McClaren]], and started McClaren's first match in charge, a friendly against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] in August 2006. He scored twice in England's 4\u20130 victory. Two further goals followed in England's next match, a 5\u20130 win over [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]] in their opening qualifying match for [[UEFA Euro 2008]] on 2 September 2006. Contemporary reports suggested that Crouch was the first player ever to reach ten goals for England within a single calendar year.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/Fiver/0,,1864775,00.html|title=Passive boozing; and wild-tackling Scouser |first1=Rob |last1=Smyth |first2=Paul |last2=Doyle |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=4 September 2006 |accessdate=4 September 2006}}</ref> In fact, this had happened several times pre-Second World War, most recently by [[Dixie Dean]] (12 goals in 1927) and [[George Camsell]] (11 goals in 1929).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamGoals/GoalsTopScorersCal.html |title=England's top scorers: Calendar year |work=England Football Online |publisher=Glen Isherwood & Peter Young |date=14 November 2017 |accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> An operation needed for a nose injury he sustained playing for Liverpool prevented him from playing in England's two qualifying matches in March 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/soccer/story/6550278|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316013932/http://msn.foxsports.com/soccer/story/6550278|archivedate=16 March 2007|title=Crouch nose he'll miss a month|publisher=Fox Sports|date=9 March 2007 |accessdate=9 March 2007}}</ref> He returned to the England squad for their matches against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] in late May and early June 2007, scoring in the qualifying match against the latter.<ref name=Estonia/> Crouch was England's top scorer in the qualifying campaign with five goals, but this did not prevent England finishing only third in their group and failing to progress to the finals of the competition.<ref name=Croatia/>\n\n===Capello era===\n[[File:Spain vs England.jpg|thumb|right|Crouch (wearing No.20) playing for England versus [[Spain national football team|Spain]], 2009]]\n\nOn 1 April 2009, Crouch made his first start under McClaren's successor, [[Fabio Capello]], in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification|2010 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]. He scored England's first goal in their 2\u20131 victory.<ref name=Ukraine/> Crouch was re-called to the England squad for the friendly against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] and the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 6|World Cup qualifier]] versus [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], following his fine form for Tottenham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8229098.stm |title=Capello recalls Crouch and Lennon |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 August 2009 |accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref> Crouch also got an early first half goal against [[Belarus national football team|Belarus]] in the final 2010 World Cup qualifier, which he then followed up with a second goal in the 76th minute.<ref name=Belarus/> This took Crouch's tally for England up to 18 goals in just 17 starts.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Peter Crouch Myth|url=http://www.ongoalsscored.com/2011/08/07/the-peter-crouch-myth/|website=On Goals Scored|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> Crouch scored a brace after coming on as a substitute against [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] in a friendly on 3 March 2010 to take his overall international goal tally to 20.<ref>{{cite web |title=England in fine fettle thanks to Crouch|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=1456964.html|publisher=UEFA|date=3 March 2010|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref> He also scored the second goal for England against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 24 May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=England 3\u20131 Mexico|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8699042.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2010 World Cup===\nCrouch was named in Capello's final 23-man squad for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] and was given the number 9 shirt.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Cup 2010: England announce squad numbers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8720235.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> He came on as a substitute for [[Emile Heskey]] in England's opening match against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] and also came off the bench for [[Gareth Barry]] in the following match against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]].<ref>{{cite web|title=England 1\u20131 USA|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_05|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=England 0\u20130 Algeria|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_23|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> Crouch did not take part in the final group stage match with Slovenia or the 4\u20131 loss to [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Germany vs England|last-16]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Slovenia 0\u20131 England|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_37|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Germany 4\u20131 England|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_51|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Post-2010 World Cup===\nCrouch came on as a substitute in the home friendly against France for the injured Steven Gerrard on 17 November 2010. He scored quickly from an [[Ashley Young]] corner to make the score 1\u20132 with an angled side-footed volley. It was his second touch of the ball.<ref name=France/> After not making an appearance for England for almost a year, Crouch stated in October 2011 that he \"does not carry much hope\" of receiving a call-up.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stoke City's Peter Crouch fears for England future|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15275354.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2011|date=12 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring a run of good form in September 2017, Crouch said in a television interview that he was not officially retired from international football.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hafez|first1=Shamoon|title=Premier League stats: Harry Kane, Man Utd, Man City, Arsene Wenger, Roy Hodgson|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41456051|accessdate=2 October 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personality as a footballer==\n===Nicknames===\nAlthough generally known as \"Crouchy,\" other nicknames he has been given by fans and the media in England have included \"RoboCrouch\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldcup.itv.com/News/Story_Page/0,15843,8607_1277794,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061029235019/http://worldcup.itv.com/News/Story_Page/0%2C15843%2C8607_1277794%2C00.html |archivedate=29 October 2006 |title=RoboCrouch out of operation? |publisher=ITV |date=13 June 2006 |accessdate=17 January 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and \"Crouchinho\" (an ironic use of the \"-[[inho]]\" suffix, meaning \"little\" in Portuguese and used by many Brazilian footballers).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sport.guardian.co.uk/columnists/story/0,,1881581,00.html|title=Crouch on the couch |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |first=Simon|last=Hattenstone|date=27 September 2006 |accessdate=17 January 2007}}</ref> He has been also referred to as \"[[Mr. Roboto]]\" by [[Univision]]'s commentators and as \"Pantera Rosa\" (\"[[The Pink Panther (character)|Pink Panther]]\") by [[Fox Sports en Espa\u00f1ol]] commentators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.foxsports.com/blogs/Nick_Webster/2006/09/03/Pantera_RosaEnglands_not_so_secret_weapon|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415175323/http://community.foxsports.com/Nick_Webster/blog/2006/09/03/Pantera_RosaEnglands_not_so_secret_weapon|archivedate=15 April 2012|title='Pantera Rosa'... England's not so secret weapon! |first=Nick |last=Webster |publisher=Fox Sports |date=3 September 2006 |accessdate=17 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Robotic dancing===\nIn the summer of 2006, Crouch adopted a robotic dancing [[goal celebration]].<ref name=\"Robot\"/> A parody of a dance he had been seen performing on a television programme covering a party held at England teammate [[David Beckham]]'s house, he first performed it after his goal for England against Hungary on 30 May. He again performed the dance after both of his first two goals against Jamaica on 3 June. The ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' newspaper wrote that the dance was inspired by the lyrics to the [[Arctic Monkeys]]' hit single \"[[I Bet You Look Good on the Dancefloor]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=17164877&method=full&siteid=94762&headline=one-bets-one-looks-good-on-the-dancefloor--name_page.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509143121/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid%3D17164877%26method%3Dfull%26siteid%3D115875%26headline%3Done-bets-one-looks-good-on-the-dancefloor--name_page.html |archivedate= 9 May 2011 |first1=Martin |last1=Lipton |first2=Paul |last2=Byrne |title=World Cup Willie |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=2 June 2006 |accessdate=2 June 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June, Crouch announced he would perform his robotic dance again only if England were to win the World Cup, saying, \"It's not about robotic dancing. It is about scoring goals and winning matches. It's an important time for everyone now.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/teams/england/5072314.stm|title=Crouch halts robotic celebrations|publisher=BBC |date=12 June 2006 |accessdate=13 June 2006|first=Phil|last=McNulty}}</ref> In September 2006, he was quoted in ''[[The Observer]]'' newspaper as saying that, \"It was funny at the time, but I didn't want to carry on doing it until it became unfunny. I've stopped doing it for the time being, but if I ever score a really big goal you never know.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/comment/story/0,,1863698,00.html|title=Confident Crouch happy to be plan B |first=Paul |last=Wilson |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |date=3 September 2006 |accessdate=3 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2007, Crouch said he would never use the robot dance again unless he scored in the UEFA Champions League Final, but he partially reprised it on 1 April 2009 after scoring during England's World Cup qualifier against Ukraine after a Comic Relief sketch.<ref name=\"Robot\">{{cite news  |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/5094114/Peter-Crouchs-robot-dance-and-the-10-funniest-goal-celebrations.html |title=Peter Crouch's robot dance and the 10 funniest goal celebrations|last=Wilson|first=Steve|date=2 April 2009 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2017, Crouch gave the dance a final outing to celebrate his 100th Premier League goal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38835628|title=Peter Crouch: Stoke striker 'emotional' to reach 100-goal Premier League milestone |date=2 February 2017 |accessdate=2 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCrouch and model [[Abbey Clancy]] married on 30 June 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title= Abbey Clancy marries Peter Crouch | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/abbey-clancy-marries-peter-crouch-2305402.html | location=London | newspaper=The Independent | first=Bang | last=Showbiz | date=1 July 2011}}</ref> Together they have two daughters and two sons, Sophia Ruby (born March 2011), Liberty Rose (born June 2015), Johnny (born January 2018)<ref>{{cite web |title=Baby joy for Abbey Clancy & Peter Crouch |url=http://www.mrpaparazzi.com/post/14425/Its-a-girl-Baby-joy-for-Abbey-Clancy--Peter-Crouch-as-they-welcome-their-first-child.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329125630/http://www.mrpaparazzi.com/post/14425/Its-a-girl-Baby-joy-for-Abbey-Clancy--Peter-Crouch-as-they-welcome-their-first-child.aspx|archivedate=29 March 2012|work=Mr Paparazzi|accessdate=15 March 2011|date=15 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gosling |first1=Francesca |title=Abbey Clancy and Peter Crouch introduce new son with social media snap |url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/celebrity/abbey-clancy-and-peter-crouch-introduce-new-son-with-social-media-snap/ar-BBHTzLg?li=BBoPWjQ&ocid=mailsignout |website=www.msn.com |publisher=Microsoft News |accessdate=20 November 2018 |date=5 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120135738/https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/celebrity/abbey-clancy-and-peter-crouch-introduce-new-son-with-social-media-snap/ar-BBHTzLg?li=BBoPWjQ&ocid=mailsignout |archive-date=20 November 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and Jack (born June 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heart.co.uk/showbiz/celebrities/abbey-clancy-give-birth-baby-peter-crouch-children/|title=When did Abbey Clancy have her baby and what has she called him?|website=Heart|language=en|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, Crouch was found guilty of [[Speed limit|speeding]] in November 2011 and ordered to pay a fine of \u00a31,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stoke City star Peter Crouch hit with \u00a31,000 speeding fine|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/story-16739585-detail/story.html?|newspaper=The Sentinel |location=Stoke-on-Trent |accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref> On 16 October 2012, Crouch was disqualified from driving for six months.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stoke City star Peter Crouch handed driving ban|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/story-17099654-detail/story.html?|newspaper=The Sentinel |location=Stoke-on-Trent |accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nCrouch released his autobiography in 2007, titled ''Walking Tall \u2013 My Story''.<ref name=\"Walking Tall\"/> His second book, ''How to be a Footballer'', was released in 2018.<ref>{{cite book|last=Crouch|first=Peter|title=How to be a Footballer|date=2018|publisher=Ebury Press|isbn=978-1785039768}}</ref> In Autumn 2018, the first series of ''That Peter Crouch Podcast'' aired, featuring Crouch along with [[Tom Fordyce]] and [[Chris Stark]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=The natural charms of Peter Crouch shine through on his podcast |first=Antonia |last=Quirke |work=New Statesman |date=21 November 2018 |accessdate=5 January 2019 |url= https://www.newstatesman.com/2018/11/that-peter-crouch-podcast-review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=That Peter Crouch Podcast |publisher=BBC Radio 5 live |accessdate=5 January 2019 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p06kyljg/episodes/downloads}}</ref>\n\nCrouch has a [[General National Vocational Qualification|GNVQ]] in Leisure and Tourism, which he obtained as part of a mandatory educational programme while at Tottenham Hotspur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p07605ss|title=That Peter Crouch Podcast, That Dreams Episode|publisher=BBC Radio 5 Live|access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Europe\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n|[[1999\u20132000 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|1999\u20132000]]<ref name=sb9900>{{soccerbase season|21235|1999|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]] (loan)\n|[[1999\u20132000 Isthmian League#Premier Division|1999\u20132000]]<ref name=NFT/>\n|[[Isthmian League]] Premier Division\n|6||1||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||6||1\n|-\n|[[IFK H\u00e4ssleholm]] (loan)\n|[[2000 Swedish football Division 2|2000]]<ref name=NFT/>\n|[[Division 2 (Swedish football)|Swedish Division 2]]\n|8||3||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||8||3\n|-\n|[[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]\n|[[20